802.11b-1999|b]]/[[IEEE 802.11g-2003|g]]/[[IEEE 802.11n-2009|n]]/[[IEEE 802.11ac|ac]]), [[Bluetooth#Bluetooth v5.0|Bluetooth 5.0]], [[near field communication|NFC]], [[GPS]], [[GLONASS]], [[Galileo (satellite navigation)|Galileo]] & [[QZSS]]}}\n{{Collapsible list|title='''Model A1865:'''\n|1=[[TD-SCDMA]] 1900 (F), 2000 (A) & [[CDMA2000]] [[Evolution-Data Optimized|EV-DO]] Rev. A (800, 1900, 2100&nbsp;MHz)}}\n| modem        = '''Models A1865/1902:''' Qualcomm MDM9655 Snapdragon X16 LTE <br />'''Model A1901:''' Intel XMM 7480\n| other        = [[IP Code|IP67]] IEC standard 60529 (splash, water, and dust resistant), [[Qi (standard)|Qi]] wireless charging, [[USB-C]] to [[Lightning (connector)]] fast charging<ref>{{cite web |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/09/13/iphone-8-iphone-x-fast-charge-usb-c-buy/ |title=iPhone 8 and iPhone X fast charge battery to 50% in 30 minutes, if you buy USB-C power adapter|accessdate=November 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111032244/https://9to5mac.com/2017/09/13/iphone-8-iphone-x-fast-charge-usb-c-buy/ |archivedate=November 11, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n| sar          = '''Model A1865:''' Head: 1.09 W/kg<br />Body: 1.17 W/kg<ref name=sar1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/legal/rfexposure/iphone10,3/en/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108152044/https://www.apple.com/legal/rfexposure/iphone10,3/en/|url-status=dead|title=Legal - RF Exposure - Apple|archivedate=November 8, 2017|website=Apple Legal}}</ref><br />'''Model A1901:''' Head: 1.08 W/kg<br />Body: 1.17 W/kg<ref name=sar>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/legal/rfexposure/iphone10,6/en/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171108205328/https://www.apple.com/legal/rfexposure/iphone10,6/en/|url-status=dead|title=Legal - RF Exposure - Apple|archivedate=November 8, 2017|website=Apple Legal}}</ref><br />'''Model A1902:''' Head: 1.12 W/kg<br />Body: 1.19 W/kg<ref name=sar1/>\n| hac          = M3, T4\n| website = {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101090839/https://www.apple.com/iphone-x/|title=iPhone X - Apple|date=November 1, 2017}}\n| references   =\n}}\n\n{{iPhone models}}\nThe '''iPhone X''' ([[Roman numerals|Roman numeral]] \"X\" pronounced \"ten\")<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/12/16297876/how-to-pronounce-iphone-x|title=It's pronounced 'iPhone Ten'|work=The Verge|access-date=October 10, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010210618/https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/12/16297876/how-to-pronounce-iphone-x|archivedate=October 10, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=You\u2019re pronouncing the iPhone X wrong |url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/gadgets/mobile-phones/awkward-iphone-x-mistake-with-people-pronouncing-the-model-wrong/news-story/43dbe90dfb2c83fdb229ede77627abfa |website=News.com.au |accessdate=12 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215222811/https://www.news.com.au/technology/gadgets/mobile-phones/awkward-iphone-x-mistake-with-people-pronouncing-the-model-wrong/news-story/43dbe90dfb2c83fdb229ede77627abfa |archive-date=December 15, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> is a [[smartphone]] designed, developed, and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is the [[List of iOS devices|eleventh]] generation of the [[iPhone]] and was announced on September 12, 2017, alongside the [[iPhone 8|iPhone 8 and iPhone 8 Plus]], at the [[Steve Jobs Theater]] in the [[Apple Park]] campus. It was available to pre-order on October 27, 2017 and was released on November 3, 2017.\n\nThe iPhone X was intended to showcase what Apple considered the technology of the future. Using a glass and stainless-steel form factor and \"[[bezel (screen)|bezel-less]]\" design, shrinking the bezels, and not having a \"chin\", unlike many Android phones.  It was the first iPhone to use an [[OLED]] screen. The home button was replaced with a new type of authentication called [[Face ID]], which used sensors to [[Facial recognition system|scan the user's face]] to unlock the device. This face-recognition capability also enabled emojis to be animated following the user's expression (Animoji). With a bezel-less design, iPhone user interaction changed significantly, using gestures to navigate the operating system rather than the home button used in all previous iPhones. At the time of its November 2017 launch, its price tag of $999 USD also made it the most expensive iPhone ever, with even higher prices internationally due to additional local sales and import taxes.\n\nThe iPhone X received generally positive reviews. Its display and build quality were widely praised, and the camera also scored positively on tests. The phone received polarized reception due to the sensor housing \"[[notch (engineering)|notch]]\" at the top of the screen and the introduction of an all-new authentication method. The notch was heavily mocked by users on social media, although app developers responded either neutrally or positively to the changes it brought to the user experience in their apps and games. Reviewers had mixed reactions, with some condemning it and others acknowledging it as unusual in the first moments of use before getting accustomed to its presence. [[Face ID]] facial recognition was praised for its simple setup, but criticized for requiring direct eyes on the screen, though that option can be disabled within the [[system preferences]].\n\nAlong with the [[iPhone 6s]], its Plus variant, and the [[iPhone SE]], the iPhone X was discontinued on September 12, 2018 following the announcement of the new [[iPhone XS|iPhone XS, iPhone XS Max]] and [[iPhone XR]] devices. As a result, with a shelf life of just over 10 months, the iPhone X had the shortest ever tenure as the flagship device in the history of the iPhone.\n\nOn November 22, 2018, Apple reportedly resumed production of the iPhone X due to weak sales of its successors. The iPhone X remains discontinued,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/platform/amp/2018/11/22/18107795/iphone-x-production-resumed-weak-demand-2018-models-rumor|title=Apple resumes iPhone X production in face of weak XS sales, report claims|website=www.theverge.com|language=en|accessdate=2018-11-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181124054926/https://www.theverge.com/platform/amp/2018/11/22/18107795/iphone-x-production-resumed-weak-demand-2018-models-rumor|archive-date=November 24, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but as of February 2019, Apple started selling refurbished models starting at $769.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/good-deals/2019/2/4/18211100/apple-iphone-x-refurbished-xr-store|title=Apple is selling refurbished iPhone X models starting at $769|website=theverge.com|language=en|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, Apple reduced the price to $599.\n\n==History==\nThe technology behind the iPhone X was in development for five years, as far back as 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Swider|first=Matt|title=Apple's Jony Ive reveals iPhone X was in development for 5 years|url=http://www.techradar.com/news/apples-jony-ive-reveals-iphone-x-was-in-development-for-5-years|work=TechRadar|accessdate=October 8, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171007073016/http://www.techradar.com/news/apples-jony-ive-reveals-iphone-x-was-in-development-for-5-years|archivedate=October 7, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Rumors of a drastic iPhone redesign began circulating around the time of iPhone 7 announcement in the third quarter of 2016,<ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=Apple to Eliminate Home Button in 2017 iPhone |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2016/08/25/apple-to-eliminate-home-button-in-2017-iphone/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005143/https://www.macrumors.com/2016/08/25/apple-to-eliminate-home-button-in-2017-iphone/ |archivedate=November 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Mitchell |last=Broussard |title=2017 iPhone Will Include Edge-to-Edge Display With 'Virtual Button' Built Into Screen |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2016/09/13/2017-iphone-virtual-button/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=September 13, 2016 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110061618/https://www.macrumors.com/2016/09/13/2017-iphone-virtual-button/ |archivedate=November 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and intensified when a [[HomePod]] firmware leak in July 2017 suggested that Apple would shortly release a phone with a nearly bezel-less design, lack of a physical home button, facial recognition, and other new features.<ref>{{cite news|last=Estes|first=Adam Clark|title=Looks Like Apple Leaked Details of the New iPhone in the HomePod Firmware [Updated]|url=https://gizmodo.com/looks-like-apple-leaked-details-of-the-new-iphone-in-th-1797393122|work=Gizmodo|accessdate=September 13, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911072531/http://gizmodo.com/looks-like-apple-leaked-details-of-the-new-iphone-in-th-1797393122|archivedate=September 11, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A near-final development version of the [[iOS 11]] operating system was also leaked in September 2017, confirming the new design and features.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/09/09/ios-11-golden-master-leaked/|title=Leaked iOS 11 GM Reveals iPhone 8 Features, Hints at LTE Apple Watch R|access-date=September 20, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910230218/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/09/09/ios-11-golden-master-leaked/|archivedate=September 10, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn August 31, 2017, Apple invited journalists to a September 12 press event,<ref>{{cite news|last=Don|first=Reisinger|title=Apple Officially Announces Big iPhone Event for September|url=http://fortune.com/2017/08/31/apple-iphone-2017/|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=Fortune|date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906161356/http://fortune.com/2017/08/31/apple-iphone-2017/|archivedate=September 6, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Darrell|first=Etherington|title=Apple sets iPhone event for September 12 at new Steve Jobs theater|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/08/31/apple-sets-iphone-event-for-september-12-at-new-steve-jobs-theater/|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=TechCrunch|date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910130430/https://techcrunch.com/2017/08/31/apple-sets-iphone-event-for-september-12-at-new-steve-jobs-theater/|archivedate=September 10, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> the first public event held at the Steve Jobs Theater on the company's new Apple Park campus in [[Cupertino, California]].<ref>{{cite news|last=David|first=Pierce|title=Apple's Next iPhone Comes September 12 on Apple's New Campus|url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-iphone-event-september-12/|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=Wired|date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911220725/https://www.wired.com/story/apple-iphone-event-september-12|archivedate=September 11, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mike|first=Murphy|title=Apple's next iPhone event will be held on Sept. 12|url=https://qz.com/1066959/the-iphone-8-will-be-unveiled-by-apple-on-sept-12-2017-official-invites-sent-out-aapl/|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=Quartz|date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906013702/https://qz.com/1066959/the-iphone-8-will-be-unveiled-by-apple-on-sept-12-2017-official-invites-sent-out-aapl/|archivedate=September 6, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lisa|first=Eadicicco|title=Here's When Apple's Big iPhone 8 Event Is Happening|url=http://time.com/4921797/apple-iphone-8-announcement-date-2017/|accessdate=September 13, 2017|work=Time|date=August 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908143409/http://time.com/4921797/apple-iphone-8-announcement-date-2017/|archivedate=September 8, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The iPhone X was unveiled during that keynote. Its US$999 starting price is the most expensive iPhone launch price.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gajanan|first1=Mahita|title=The iPhone X Is the Most Expensive Smartphone Apple's Ever Made|url=http://time.com/4937143/iphone-x-8-price-cost/|website=Time|accessdate=September 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920031337/http://time.com/4937143/iphone-x-8-price-cost/|archivedate=September 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The price is even higher in international markets due to currency fluctuations, [[Tariff|import fees]] and [[Value-added tax|sales taxes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=How expensive is the most expensive iPhone in other countries?|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/13/16301450/apple-iphone-x-prices-most-expensive-world|website=The Verge|accessdate=September 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922100153/https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/13/16301450/apple-iphone-x-prices-most-expensive-world|archivedate=September 22, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAn unlocked version of the phone was made available for purchase in the United States on December 5, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |first=Valentina |last=Palladino |title=Apple now offers unlocked iPhone X models in the US |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2017/12/apple-now-offers-unlocked-iphone-x-models-in-the-us/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=December 5, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205142207/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2017/12/apple-now-offers-unlocked-iphone-x-models-in-the-us/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Todd |last=Haselton |title=Apple launches an iPhone X that's not tied to a wireless carrier |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/05/unlocked-iphone-x-was-quietly-launched-overnight.html |website=[[CNBC]] |publisher=[[NBCUniversal News Group]] |date=December 5, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206074548/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/12/05/unlocked-iphone-x-was-quietly-launched-overnight.html |archive-date=December 6, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, the Federal Communications Commission divulged images of an unreleased gold-colored iPhone X model.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2018/4/13/17235708/apple-gold-iphone-x-photos-fcc|title=Apple\u2019s unreleased gold iPhone X revealed by FCC|last=Welch|first=Chris|website=The Verge|date=April 15, 2018|accessdate=April 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415051832/https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2018/4/13/17235708/apple-gold-iphone-x-photos-fcc|archive-date=April 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> As opposed to the space gray and silver color options that the iPhone X ships with, it was divulged that there were initial plans to release a gold option for the device. However, it was put on hold due to production issues.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/apple-gold-iphone-x/|title=Unreleased gold iPhone X leaked|last=Smith|first=Jake|website=ZDNet|date=April 15, 2018|accessdate=April 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415050154/https://www.zdnet.com/article/apple-gold-iphone-x/|archive-date=April 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nApple released a revised B model for the iPhone X that fixed [[Near-field communication|NFC]] issues for users in Japan, China, and the United States.<ref name=\"Breckinridge Bassett\">{{cite web |first=Joel |last=Breckinridge Bassett |title=iPhone X Suica problem |url=https://atadistance.net/2018/07/26/iphone-x-suica-problem-qa/ |website=atadistance |date=July 26, 2018 |accessdate=October 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018003020/https://atadistance.net/2018/07/26/iphone-x-suica-problem-qa/ |archive-date=October 18, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>                                     \n\n<br />\n\n==Specifications==\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone X has a 5.85 inch (marketed as 5.8 inch) OLED color-accurate screen that supports [[DCI-P3]] wide color gamut, sRGB, and [[high dynamic range]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Mitchel |last=Broussard |title=DisplayMate: iPhone X Has the 'Most Innovative and High Performance' Smartphone Display Ever Tested |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/06/displaymate-iphone-x-display/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=November 6, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110061640/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/06/displaymate-iphone-x-display/ |archivedate=November 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Samuel |last=Axon |title=Hands on with the iPhone X: OLED and HDR outshine the other features |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2017/09/hands-on-with-the-iphone-x-oled-and-hdr-outshine-everything-else/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930231055/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2017/09/hands-on-with-the-iphone-x-oled-and-hdr-outshine-everything-else/ |archivedate=September 30, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and has a contrast ratio of 1,000,000:1.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Smith |title=This is what you're giving up if you buy an iPhone 8 or iPhone 8 Plus tomorrow |url=http://bgr.com/2017/09/14/iphone-x-vs-iphone-8-plus-vs-iphone-8-specs-differences/ |website=[[Boy Genius Report|BGR]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=September 14, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110114742/http://bgr.com/2017/09/14/iphone-x-vs-iphone-8-plus-vs-iphone-8-specs-differences/ |archivedate=November 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Super Retina display has the True Tone technology found on the [[iPad Pro]], which uses [[ambient light sensor]]s to adapt the display's white balance to the surrounding ambient light.<ref name=\"Announcement\">{{cite web |first=Vlad |last=Savov |title=iPhone X announced with edge-to-edge screen, Face ID, and no home button |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16288806/apple-iphone-x-price-release-date-features-announced |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021084526/https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16288806/apple-iphone-x-price-release-date-features-announced |archivedate=October 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chaim |last=Gartenberg |title=iPhone 8 and 8 Plus announced with wireless charging, True Tone display, A11 Bionic processor |url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/12/16277764/apple-iphone-8-announced-features-price-release-date |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011182101/https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/12/16277764/apple-iphone-8-announced-features-price-release-date |archivedate=October 11, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Although the iPhone X does not feature the same \"ProMotion\" technology used in the displays of the second-generation [[iPad Pro]], where the display delivers a refresh rate of 120&nbsp;Hz, it does sample touch input at 120&nbsp;Hz.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3235709/iphone-ipad/iphone-x-samples-touch-input-at-120hz-for-faster-smoother-response.html|title=iPhone X samples touch input at 120Hz for faster, smoother response|work=Macworld|access-date=November 16, 2017|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116132240/https://www.macworld.com/article/3235709/iphone-ipad/iphone-x-samples-touch-input-at-120hz-for-faster-smoother-response.html|archive-date=November 16, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> OLED screen technology has a known negative trend of \"burn-in\" effects, in which particular elements consistently on the screen for long periods of time leave a faint trace even after new images appear. Apple acknowledged that its OLED screens were not excluded from this issue, writing in a support document that \"This is also expected behavior\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Liam |last=Tung |title=iPhone X: We can reduce but not eliminate burn-in on OLED screen, says Apple |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/iphone-x-we-can-reduce-but-not-eliminate-burn-in-on-oled-screen-says-apple/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=November 6, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203154624/http://www.zdnet.com/article/iphone-x-we-can-reduce-but-not-eliminate-burn-in-on-oled-screen-says-apple/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Zac |last=Hall |title=Apple says color and hue shifting, OLED burn-in expected on iPhone X |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/11/03/iphone-x-oled-burn-in-color-shifting/ |website=9to5Mac |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206135852/https://9to5mac.com/2017/11/03/iphone-x-oled-burn-in-color-shifting/ |archive-date=December 6, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Greg Joswiak, Apple's vice president of product marketing, told ''[[Tom's Hardware|Tom's Guide]]'' that the OLED panels Apple used in the iPhone X had been engineered to avoid the \"oversaturation\" of colors that using OLED panels typically results in, having made color adjustments and \"subpixel\"-level refinements for crisp lines and round corners.<ref>{{cite web |title=Most Innovative Tech of 2017 |url=https://www.tomsguide.com/us/innovation-awards-2017,review-4938.html |website=[[Tom's Hardware]] |publisher=[[Purch Group]] |date=December 6, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231401/https://www.tomsguide.com/us/innovation-awards-2017,review-4938.html |archive-date=December 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=Apple's Greg Joswiak Talks iPhone X Face ID, Display and A11 Chip |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/12/06/apples-greg-joswiak-talks-iphone-x/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=December 6, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208175128/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/12/06/apples-greg-joswiak-talks-iphone-x/ |archive-date=December 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> For out-of-warranty servicing for damages not relating to manufacturing defects, screen repairs of iPhone X cost US$279, while other damage repairs cost US$549.<ref>{{cite web |first=Joe |last=Rossignol |title=Apple to Charge $279 for iPhone X Screen Repairs and $549 for Other Damage Outside of Warranty |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/10/27/iphone-x-screen-repair-out-of-warranty-fees/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=October 27, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206135954/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/10/27/iphone-x-screen-repair-out-of-warranty-fees/ |archive-date=December 6, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jacob |last=Kastrenakes |title=iPhone X screen repair will cost $279 |url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/10/27/16556934/iphone-x-screen-repair-costs-out-of-warranty |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 27, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040819/https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/10/27/16556934/iphone-x-screen-repair-costs-out-of-warranty |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone X has two color options; silver and space gray.<ref name=\"Announcement\" /> The sides of the phone are composed of surgical-grade stainless steel to improve durability, and the front and back are made of glass. The design is intended to be [[IP Code|IP67]] water and dust resistant.<ref name=\"Announcement\" /><ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Crook |title=This is the iPhone X |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/12/iphone-x/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109023207/https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/12/iphone-x/ |archivedate=November 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone X contains Apple's [[Apple A11|A11 Bionic]] [[System-on-a-chip|system-on-chip]], also used in the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus, which is a six-core processor with two cores optimized for performance (25% faster than the [[Apple A10|A10 Fusion]] processor), along with four cores optimized for efficiency (70% faster than the previous generation).<ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=A11 Bionic Chip in iPhone 8 and iPhone X on Par With 13-Inch MacBook Pro, Outperforms iPad Pro |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/09/13/a11-bionic-chip-geekbench-scores/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929104814/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/09/13/a11-bionic-chip-geekbench-scores/ |archivedate=September 29, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It also features the first Apple-designed [[graphics processing unit]]<ref>{{cite web |first=Matthew |last=Lynley |title=The new iPhone 8 has a custom GPU designed by Apple with its new A11 Bionic chip |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/12/the-new-iphone-8-has-a-custom-gpu-designed-by-apple-with-its-new-a11-bionic-chip/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045638/https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/12/the-new-iphone-8-has-a-custom-gpu-designed-by-apple-with-its-new-a11-bionic-chip/ |archive-date=September 24, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Wuerthele |title=A11 Bionic processor in iPhone 8, iPhone X contains first Apple-designed GPU, new secure element |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/09/15/a11-bionic-processor-in-iphone-8-iphone-x-contains-first-apple-designed-gpu-new-secure-element |website=AppleInsider |date=September 15, 2017 |accessdate=December 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206074513/http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/09/15/a11-bionic-processor-in-iphone-8-iphone-x-contains-first-apple-designed-gpu-new-secure-element |archive-date=December 6, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and a [[Apple Neural Engine|Neural Engine]], which powers an [[artificial intelligence]] accelerator.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Simonite |title=Apple's 'neural engine' infuses the iPhone with AI smarts |url=https://www.wired.com/story/apples-neural-engine-infuses-the-iphone-with-ai-smarts/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930174333/https://www.wired.com/story/apples-neural-engine-infuses-the-iphone-with-ai-smarts/ |archivedate=September 30, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=The iPhone X's new neural engine exemplifies Apple's approach to AI |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/13/16300464/apple-iphone-x-ai-neural-engine |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915010751/https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/13/16300464/apple-iphone-x-ai-neural-engine |archivedate=September 15, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Face ID]] replaces the Touch ID authentication system. The [[facial recognition system|facial recognition]] sensor consists of two parts: a \"Romeo\" module that projects more than 30,000 infrared dots onto the user's face, and a \"Juliet\" module that reads the pattern.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-iphone-x-production-woe-sparked-by-juliet-and-her-romeo-1506510189|title=Apple iPhone X Production Woe Sparked by Juliet and Her Romeo|last=Kubota|first=Yoko|date=September 27, 2017|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=September 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928103032/https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-iphone-x-production-woe-sparked-by-juliet-and-her-romeo-1506510189|archive-date=September 28, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The pattern is sent to the Secure Enclave in the A11 Bionic chip to confirm a match with the phone owner's face.<ref name=\"Biggest questions\">{{cite web |first=Russell |last=Brandom |title=The five biggest questions about Apple's new facial recognition system |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16298156/apple-iphone-x-face-id-security-privacy-police-unlock |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115005812/https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16298156/apple-iphone-x-face-id-security-privacy-police-unlock |archivedate=November 15, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Alfred |last=Ng |title=Is Face ID secure? Apple takes on lingering questions |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-takes-on-some-unanswered-questions-about-face-id/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=September 27, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002101520/https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-takes-on-some-unanswered-questions-about-face-id/ |archivedate=October 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> By default, the system will not work with eyes closed, in an effort to prevent unauthorized access but this requirement can be disabled in settings.<ref name=\"Biggest questions\" />\n\nThe iPhone X has two cameras on the rear. One is a 12-megapixel [[Wide-angle lens|wide-angle]] camera with f/1.8 [[f-number|aperture]], with support for [[face detection]], [[high dynamic range]] and [[optical image stabilization]]. It is capable of capturing [[4K resolution|4K]] video at 24, 30 or 60 [[Frame rate|frames per second]], or 1080p video at 30, 60, 120 or 240 frames per second.<ref name=\"GSMArena\">{{cite web |title=Apple iPhone X |url=https://www.gsmarena.com/apple_iphone_x-8858.php |website=GSMArena |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930181638/http://www.gsmarena.com/apple_iphone_x-8858.php |archivedate=September 30, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A secondary, [[telephoto]] lens features 2\u00d7 optical zoom and 10\u00d7 digital zoom with an aperture of f/2.4 and optical image stabilization.<ref name=\"CNET cameras\">{{cite web |first1=Vanessa Hand |last1=Orellana |first2=Lexy |last2=Savvides |title=iPhone X vs iPhone 8 Plus: Is the camera that much better? |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/iphone-x-vs-iphone-8-plus-is-the-camera-worth-the-money/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=November 6, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109125453/https://www.cnet.com/news/iphone-x-vs-iphone-8-plus-is-the-camera-worth-the-money/ |archivedate=November 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A Portrait Mode is capable of producing photos with specific depth-of-field and lighting effects.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jordan |last=Bishop |title=The iPhone X Is Poised To Replace DSLR Cameras |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/bishopjordan/2017/10/19/iphone-x-camera-replace-dslr-travel-camera-wide-angle-telephoto-portrait-mode-lighting-face-id/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=October 19, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110011645/https://www.forbes.com/sites/bishopjordan/2017/10/19/iphone-x-camera-replace-dslr-travel-camera-wide-angle-telephoto-portrait-mode-lighting-face-id/ |archivedate=November 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> It also has a quad-LED [[Flash (photography)|True Tone flash]] with 2\u00d7 better light uniformity.<ref>{{cite web |title=The future is here: iPhone X |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/09/the-future-is-here-iphone-x/ |website=Apple Newsroom |publisher=[[Apple Inc.]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924073859/https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/09/the-future-is-here-iphone-x/ |archivedate=September 24, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn the front of the phone, a 7-megapixel TrueDepth camera has an f/2.2 aperture,<ref name=\"CNET cameras\" /> and features face detection and HDR. It can capture 1080p video at 30 frames per second, 720p video at 240 frames per second,<ref name=\"GSMArena\" /> and exclusively allows for the use of [[Animoji]]; animated emojis placed on top of the user's face that intelligently react to the user's facial expressions.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jason |last=Cipriani |title=Here's what you need to know about animoji |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/getting-started-with-the-iphone-x-animoji-apple/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=November 7, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109063706/https://www.cnet.com/how-to/getting-started-with-the-iphone-x-animoji-apple/ |archivedate=November 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Tom |last=Warren |title=Apple announces Animoji, animated emoji for iPhone X |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16290210/new-iphone-emoji-animated-animoji-apple-ios-11-update |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928182447/https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16290210/new-iphone-emoji-animated-animoji-apple-ios-11-update |archivedate=September 28, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\niPhone X also supports [[Qi (standard)|Qi-standard]] [[wireless charging]].<ref name=\"Announcement\" /> In tests conducted by ''[[MacRumors]]'', the iPhone X's charging speed varies significantly depending on what types of cables, powerbanks, adapters, or wireless chargers are used.<ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=iPhone X Charging Speeds Compared: The Fastest and Easiest Ways to Charge Your iPhone |url=https://www.macrumors.com/guide/iphone-x-fast-charging-speeds-compared/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=December 5, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207233849/https://www.macrumors.com/guide/iphone-x-fast-charging-speeds-compared/ |archive-date=December 7, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Software===\n{{See also|iOS version history|iOS 11|iOS 12|iOS 13}}\nDue to its different screen layout, iOS developers are required to update their apps to make full use of the additional screen real estate. Such changes include rounded corners, sensor \"notch\" at the top of the screen, and an indicator area at the bottom for accessing the home screen. Apple published a \"Human Interface Guidelines\" document to explain areas of focus, and discouraged developers from attempting to mask or call special attention to any of the new changes. Additionally, text within the app needs to be configured to properly reference Face ID rather than Touch ID where the authentication technology is used on iPhone X.<ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=Apple Encourages Developers to Update Their Apps for iPhone X |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/10/27/apple-developer-update-apps-iphone-x/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=October 27, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205194546/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/10/27/apple-developer-update-apps-iphone-x/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In anticipation of the release of the phone, most major apps were quickly updated to support the new changes brought by iPhone X,<ref>{{cite web |first=Joe |last=Rossignol |title=iPhone X Apps Now Widely Rolling Out on App Store Ahead of Device's Launch Tomorrow |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/02/iphone-x-ready-apps-list/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=November 2, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205194600/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/02/iphone-x-ready-apps-list/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> though the required changes did cause delayed app updates for some major apps.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chaim |last=Gartenberg |title=Google updates Docs, Slides, and Sheets for iPhone X and iOS 11 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/27/16705020/google-docs-slides-sheets-update-iphone-x-ios-11-drag-drop-support |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 27, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203120635/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/27/16705020/google-docs-slides-sheets-update-iphone-x-ios-11-drag-drop-support |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Mitchel |last=Broussard |title=Google Introduces iPhone X Support for Docs, Sheets, and Slides iOS Apps |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/27/google-iphone-x-docs-sheets/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=November 27, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205194558/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/27/google-iphone-x-docs-sheets/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chaim |last=Gartenberg |title=Google Maps gets updated for iPhone X |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/30/16721040/google-maps-apple-iphone-x-update-finally |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 30, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203051632/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/30/16721040/google-maps-apple-iphone-x-update-finally |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe traditional home button, found on all previous devices in the iPhone lineup, has been removed entirely, replaced by touch-based gestures. To wake up the device, users can tap the display or use the side button; to access the home screen, users must swipe up from the bottom of the display; and to access the multitasking window, users must swipe up similarly to the method of accessing the home screen, but stop while the finger is in the middle of the screen, causing an app carousel to appear.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Smith |title=Every new iPhone X gesture you need to learn |url=http://bgr.com/2017/11/03/iphone-x-gestures-guide-home-button/ |website=[[Boy Genius Report|BGR]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205093058/http://bgr.com/2017/11/03/iphone-x-gestures-guide-home-button/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jason |last=Cross |title=iPhone X: Learn all the new touch gestures and commands |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3235724/iphone-ipad/iphone-x-touch-gestures-and-commands.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205194625/https://www.macworld.com/article/3235724/iphone-ipad/iphone-x-touch-gestures-and-commands.html |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n\n==Reception==\n===General reviews===\niPhone X's rear camera received an overall rating of 97 from DxOMark, a camera testing company, short of the highest score of 99, awarded to Samsung's [[Samsung Galaxy S9|Galaxy S9+]] smartphone. Google's [[Pixel 2]] received a rating of 98.<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Potuck |title=iPhone X scores 97 on DxOMark camera ranking, just behind Google Pixel 2 |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/11/06/iphone-x-scores-97-dxomark/ |website=9to5Mac |date=November 6, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005123/https://9to5mac.com/2017/11/06/iphone-x-scores-97-dxomark/ |archive-date=November 10, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/samsungs-galaxy-s9-plus-earns-best-ever-dxomark-camera-ratings/|title=Samsung's Galaxy S9 Plus earns best-ever DxOMark camera ratings|date=2018-03-01|work=CNET|access-date=2018-03-02|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302142308/https://www.cnet.com/news/samsungs-galaxy-s9-plus-earns-best-ever-dxomark-camera-ratings/|archive-date=March 2, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Consumer Reports]], a non-profit, independent organization aiming to write impartial reviews of consumer products, ranked iPhone X below [[iPhone 8|iPhone 8 and iPhone 8 Plus]], as well as below [[Samsung]]'s [[Galaxy S8|Galaxy S8, S8+]] and [[Note 8]], due to less durability and shorter battery life, although it praised the X's camera as \"the highest-rated smartphone camera\" it had ever tested.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bree |last=Fowler |title=CR's Final iPhone X Test Results: Top-Scoring Camera and Display But Also Some Flaws |url=https://www.consumerreports.org/smartphones/iphone-x-review-test-results/ |website=[[Consumer Reports]] |date=December 5, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207072424/https://www.consumerreports.org/smartphones/iphone-x-review-test-results/ |archive-date=December 7, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=Consumer Reports Ranks iPhone X Below iPhone 8 Because of Durability and Battery Life |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/12/05/iphone-x-consumer-reports-ranking-below-iphone-8/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=December 5, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208231513/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/12/05/iphone-x-consumer-reports-ranking-below-iphone-8/ |archive-date=December 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nNilay Patel of ''The Verge'' praised the display, calling it \"polished and tight and clean\" and \"bright and colorful\". He criticized the repeated lack of a headphone jack, the device's fragility despite Apple's claims of durability, and the sensor notch, calling it \"ugly\". Patel highlighted the fact that apps required updates to fit the new screen, writing that not all popular apps had received updates by the time of the review, resulting in some apps with \"huge black borders\" resembling iPhone 8. He especially criticized the positioning of the sensor notch while holding the phone in landscape mode, causing the notch to go \"from being a somewhat forgettable element in the top status bar to a giant interruption on the side of the screen\". The cameras were given positive feedback for maintaining detail in low-light. Patel particularly praised Animoji, calling it \"probably the single best feature on the iPhone X\", writing that \"they just work, and they work incredibly well\". Finally, he wrote that Face ID was the whole foundation of iPhone X, and stated that it \"generally works great\", though acknowledging the occasional misstep, in which users must \"actively move the phone closer to your face to compensate\". He specifically criticized the limited range of Face ID, with authentication only working when holding the phone 25\u201350 centimeters away from the face.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nilay |last=Patel |title=iPhone X review: face the future |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/31/16579748/apple-iphone-x-review |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205194545/https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/31/16579748/apple-iphone-x-review |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nChris Velazco of ''Engadget'' also praised the display, writing that, in his experience, the sensor \"notch\" goes from being \"weird at first\" to not being noticeable due to action in videos usually happening in the center. The build quality was given particular acclaim, being called \"a beautifully made device\" with a construction that \"seamlessly\" connects the front and back glass with the stainless-steel frame. Velazco noted that the new gesture-based interaction takes time getting used to, particularly the Control Center being moved from the bottom to the top right of the display. The camera, processor performance, and battery life were also given positive thoughts.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Velazco |title=iPhone X review: Embrace the new normal |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/03/apple-iphone-x-review/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203225232/https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/03/apple-iphone-x-review/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn a heavily negative review, Dennis Green of ''Business Insider'' significantly criticized the impossible one-handed use of iPhone X, writing that the new gestures to use the phone, such as swiping from the top down to access notifications and the Control Center, did not work when using the phone with only one hand due to not being able to reach the top.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dennis |last=Green |title=I've been using my iPhone X for nearly a month, and I've decided I hate it |url=http://nordic.businessinsider.com/iphone-x-negative-review-2017-11 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]] |date=November 24, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129045946/http://nordic.businessinsider.com/iphone-x-negative-review-2017-11 |archive-date=November 29, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> His review sparked outrage among [[Twitter]] users, many of whom used condescending tones, which Green reasoned as \"I don't know whether the anger was directed toward me out of loyalty to Apple or to justify their own choice to spend $1,000 on a phone. It was obvious that much of the criticism came from people who had never used the phone\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Dennis |last=Green |title=I wrote about how much I hate my iPhone X \u2014 and an army of Apple fans attacked me online |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/negative-iphone-x-review-sparks-uproar-2017-11 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]] |date=November 30, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203235834/http://www.businessinsider.com/negative-iphone-x-review-sparks-uproar-2017-11 |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n''Macworld''{{'}}s Roman Loyola praised the Face ID authentication system, writing that the setup process was \"easy\" and that its system integration was \"more seamless\" than the Touch ID fingerprint authentication of the past. That said, Loyola did note the \"half-second\" slower unlocking time than Touch ID as well as needing to look directly at the screen, making it impossible to unlock with the phone next to the user on a desk.<ref>{{cite web |first=Roman |last=Loyola |title=iPhone X review: The thrill is back |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3236870/iphone-ipad/iphone-x-review.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=November 14, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205194620/https://www.macworld.com/article/3236870/iphone-ipad/iphone-x-review.html |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Face ID security and privacy concerns===\nFace ID has raised concerns regarding the possibility of law enforcement accessing an individual's phone by pointing the device at the user's face.<ref>{{cite web |first=Madison Malone |last=Kircher |title=Yes, You Can Unlock the New iPhone With Your Face. Here's How It Works. |url=http://nymag.com/selectall/2017/09/face-id-unlocks-iphone-x-without-home-button-is-it-safe.html |website=Select All |publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013203938/http://nymag.com/selectall/2017/09/face-id-unlocks-iphone-x-without-home-button-is-it-safe.html |archivedate=October 13, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> United States Senator [[Al Franken]] asked Apple to provide more information on the security and privacy of Face ID a day after the announcement,<ref>{{cite web |first=Tony |last=Romm |title=Apple is facing questions from the U.S. Senate on the privacy protections in iPhone X and Face ID |url=https://www.recode.net/2017/9/13/16304932/apple-iphone-x-face-id-facial-recognition-privacy-security-franken-senate-congress |website=[[Recode]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110114541/https://www.recode.net/2017/9/13/16304932/apple-iphone-x-face-id-facial-recognition-privacy-security-franken-senate-congress |archivedate=November 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> with Apple responding by highlighting the recent publication of a security white paper and knowledge base detailing answers.<ref>{{cite web |first=Natasha |last=Lomas |title=Apple responds to Senator Franken's Face ID privacy concerns |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/17/apple-responds-to-senator-frankens-face-id-privacy-concerns/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=October 17, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109023814/https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/17/apple-responds-to-senator-frankens-face-id-privacy-concerns/ |archivedate=November 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Saqib |last=Shah |title=Apple responds to Sen. Al Franken's Face ID concerns in letter |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/18/apple-letter-senator-al-franken-face-id/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=October 18, 2017 |accessdate=November 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110005110/https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/18/apple-letter-senator-al-franken-face-id/ |archivedate=November 10, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nInconsistent results have been shown when testing Face ID on identical twins, with some tests showing the system managing to separate the two,<ref>{{cite web |first=Emmanuel |last=Ocbazghi |title=We put the iPhone X's Face ID to the ultimate test with identical twins \u2014 and the results surprised us |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/can-iphone-x-tell-difference-between-twins-face-id-recognition-apple-2017-10 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]] |date=October 31, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204224354/http://www.businessinsider.com/can-iphone-x-tell-difference-between-twins-face-id-recognition-apple-2017-10 |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> while other tests have failed.<ref>{{cite web |first=Lance |last=Ulanoff |title=The iPhone X can't tell the difference between identical twins |url=http://mashable.com/2017/10/31/putting-iphone-x-face-id-to-twin-test/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=October 31, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203130152/https://mashable.com/2017/10/31/putting-iphone-x-face-id-to-twin-test/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHowever, despite Apple's promise of increased security of Face ID compared to the Touch ID fingerprint authentication system,<ref>{{cite web |first=Tom |last=Warren |title=Apple's Face ID struggles detailed in new iPhone X report |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/25/16542614/apple-iphone-x-face-id-manufacturing-issues-report |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 25, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204223019/https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/25/16542614/apple-iphone-x-face-id-manufacturing-issues-report |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> there have been multiple media reports indicating otherwise. ''The Verge'' noted that courts in the United States have granted different Fifth Amendment rights in the United States Constitution to biometric unlocking systems as opposed to keycodes. Keycodes are considered \"testimonial\" evidence based on the contents of users' thoughts, whereas fingerprints are considered physical evidence, with some suspects having been ordered to unlock their phones via fingerprint.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adi |last=Robertson |title=Why Face ID won't give you the legal protection of a passcode |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16298192/apple-iphone-face-id-legal-security-fifth-amendment |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204223017/https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16298192/apple-iphone-face-id-legal-security-fifth-amendment |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Many attempts to break through Face ID with sophisticated masks have been attempted, though most have failed.<ref>{{cite web |first=Andy |last=Greenberg |title=We tried really hard to beat Face ID - and failed (so far) |url=https://www.wired.com/story/tried-to-beat-face-id-and-failed-so-far/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205042120/https://www.wired.com/story/tried-to-beat-face-id-and-failed-so-far/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> A week after iPhone X was released, Vietnamese security firm Bkav announced in a blog post that it had successfully created a $150 mask that tricked Face ID, though ''WIRED'' noted that Bkav's technique was more of a \"proof-of-concept\" rather than active exploitation risk, with the technique requiring a detailed measurement or digital scan of the iPhone owner's face, putting the real risk of danger only to targets of espionage and world leaders.<ref>{{cite web |first=Andy |last=Greenberg |title=Hackers say they've broken Face ID a week after iPhone X release |url=https://www.wired.com/story/hackers-say-broke-face-id-security/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=November 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205042015/https://www.wired.com/story/hackers-say-broke-face-id-security/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Thuy |last=Ong |title=This $150 mask beat Face ID on the iPhone X |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/13/16642690/bkav-iphone-x-faceid-mask |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 13, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204223014/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/13/16642690/bkav-iphone-x-faceid-mask |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, ''Reuters'' reported in early November 2017 that Apple would share certain facial data on users with third-party app developers for more precise selfie filters and for fictional game characters to mirror real-world user facial expressions. Although developers are required to seek customer permission, are not allowed to sell the data to others nor create profiles on users nor use the data for advertising, and are limited to a more \"rough map\" rather than full capabilities, they still get access to over 50 kinds of facial expressions. The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) and the Center for Democracy and Technology raised privacy questions about Apple's enforcement of the privacy restrictions connected to third-party access, with Apple maintaining that its App Store review processes were effective safeguards. The \"rough map\" of facial data third-parties can access is also not enough to unlock the device, according to ''Reuters''. However, the overall idea of letting developers access sensitive facial information was still not satisfactorily handled, according to Jay Stanley, a senior policy analyst with the ACLU, with Stanley telling ''Reuters'' that \"the privacy issues around of the use of very sophisticated facial recognition technology for unlocking the phone have been overblown. \u2026 The real privacy issues have to do with the access by third-party developers\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=Nellis |title=App developer access to iPhone X face data spooks some privacy experts |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-iphone-privacy-analysis/app-developer-access-to-iphone-x-face-data-spooks-some-privacy-experts-idUSKBN1D20DZ |website=[[Reuters]] |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |date=November 2, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205093114/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-iphone-privacy-analysis/app-developer-access-to-iphone-x-face-data-spooks-some-privacy-experts-idUSKBN1D20DZ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Statt |title=Apple will share face mapping data from the iPhone X with third-party app developers |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/2/16599592/apple-iphone-x-face-id-data-share-app-developers-privacy |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 2, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204223015/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/2/16599592/apple-iphone-x-face-id-data-share-app-developers-privacy |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Sensor housing controversy===\nMuch of the debate about the iPhone X has revolved around the design of the sensor housing, dubbed \"notch\" by the media, at the top of the display. ''The Outline'' described it as \"a visually disgusting element\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Joshua |last=Topolsky |title=Apple is really bad at design |url=https://theoutline.com/post/2352/apple-is-really-bad-at-design |website=[[The Outline (website)|The Outline]] |date=September 29, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206005836/https://theoutline.com/post/2352/apple-is-really-bad-at-design |archive-date=December 6, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and ''The Verge'' posted a report focusing on public criticism and people mocking Apple's \"odd design choice\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Tom |last=Warren |title=Apple's iPhone X notch is an odd design choice |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/14/16306298/apple-iphone-x-screen-notch |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 14, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204223008/https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/14/16306298/apple-iphone-x-screen-notch |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but not every reviewer was equally negative in their opinions. Third-party iOS developers interviewed by ''Ars Technica'' said that, despite the work of restructuring design elements in their apps, the notch did not cause any problems, with some even arguing that the notch was a good push to simplify their designs.<ref>{{cite web |first=Samuel |last=Axon |title=How app developers and designers feel about the iPhone X\u2014and the notch |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2017/11/how-devs-updated-their-apps-for-the-iphone-xs-screen-and-the-notch/2/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=November 25, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205143534/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2017/11/how-devs-updated-their-apps-for-the-iphone-xs-screen-and-the-notch/2/ |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Just two weeks after iPhone X's release, Apple approved a \"notch remover\" app through the App Store, that places black bars across the top of the home screen to make the notch visually disappear. The approval was done despite the company's user interface guidelines discouraging developers from specifically masking the design.<ref>{{cite web |first=Thomas |last=Ricker |title=iPhone X 'notch remover' now available in App Store |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/13/16642604/notch-remover-app-iphone-x |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 13, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203194642/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/13/16642604/notch-remover-app-iphone-x |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> iPhone X was not the first device with a notch\u2013both the [[Essential Phone]] and Sharp Aquos S2 were announced before it and had a display notch, but the iPhone X arguably popularized it.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidauthority.com/who-owns-the-notch-845086|title=Who owns the notch?|date=2018-03-15|work=Android Authority|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826182954/https://www.androidauthority.com/who-owns-the-notch-845086/|archive-date=August 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.phonearena.com/news/First-notch-phone-Sharp-not-Essential_id105608|title=No, the iPhone X wasn't first to market with a notch, but neither was the Essential Phone (poll results)|last=Petrov|first=Daniel|work=Phone Arena|access-date=2018-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826214515/https://www.phonearena.com/news/First-notch-phone-Sharp-not-Essential_id105608|archive-date=August 26, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Issues==\n===Early activation issues===\nIn November 2017, early adopters of the new phone reported that they were experiencing activation issues on certain cellular carriers, most notably [[AT&T]]. AT&T announced within hours that the issue had been fixed on their end, and a spokesperson for the Verizon carrier told the media none of its customers were affected despite some reports of problems.<ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=Some New iPhone X Owners Facing Activation Issues [Updated] |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/03/iphone-x-activation-issues/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=November 3, 2017 |access-date=November 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117065518/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/03/iphone-x-activation-issues/ |archive-date=November 17, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Micah |last=Singleton |title=Some iPhone X buyers are having problems activating their phones |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/3/16604392/iphone-x-activation-issues-att-verizon-apple |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 3, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171205194543/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/3/16604392/iphone-x-activation-issues-att-verizon-apple |archive-date=December 5, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Cold weather issues===\nIn November 2017, iPhone X users reported on [[Reddit]] that the device's screen would become unresponsive after experiencing rapid temperature drops.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Statt |title=Apple plans software update to fix iPhone X screen responsiveness in cold weather |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/9/16631596/apple-iphone-x-cold-weather-screen-bug-software-update |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110030420/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/9/16631596/apple-iphone-x-cold-weather-screen-bug-software-update |archive-date=November 10, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=Apple Working on Fix for Bug Causing iPhone X Display to Become Temporarily Unresponsive in Cold Weather |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/09/iphone-x-cold-weather-fix/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=November 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110071700/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/09/iphone-x-cold-weather-fix/ |archive-date=November 10, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Apple released the iOS 11.1.2 update on November 16, 2017, fixing the issue.<ref>{{cite web |first=Juli |last=Clover |title=Apple Releases iOS 11.1.2 With Fix for Unresponsive iPhone X Display in Cold Temperatures |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/16/apple-releases-ios-11-1-2/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=November 16, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118183133/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/16/apple-releases-ios-11-1-2/ |archive-date=November 18, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chaim |last=Gartenberg |title=Apple's latest iOS update fixes iPhone X screen responsiveness in cold weather |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/16/16667304/ios-11-update-iphone-x-cold-screen-unresponsive-fix-apple |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=November 16, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119081344/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/16/16667304/ios-11-update-iphone-x-cold-screen-unresponsive-fix-apple |archive-date=November 19, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nForbes contributor Gordon Kelly reported in March 2018 that over 1,000 users experienced problems using camera flash in cold weather, with the problem still persisting as of iOS 11.3 beta 1.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kelly |last=Gordon |title=Apple's New iPhones Have A Nasty Surprise |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gordonkelly/2018/03/04/apple-iphone-x-iphone-8-iphone-8-plus-camera-problem-price-upgrade/#6707eca471a1 |date=March 4, 2018 |access-date=March 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306063105/https://www.forbes.com/sites/gordonkelly/2018/03/04/apple-iphone-x-iphone-8-iphone-8-plus-camera-problem-price-upgrade/#6707eca471a1#6707eca471a1 |archive-date=March 6, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Cellular modem differences===\nApple has been engaged in a legal battle with [[Qualcomm]] over allegedly anti-competitive practices and has been dual-sourcing cellular modem chips to reduce reliance on the semiconductor manufacturer. Starting with iPhone 7 in 2016, Apple has used about half Qualcomm modem chips and half Intel.<ref>{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Pressman |title=What Qualcomm Chips Do and Why Apple Ditching Them Would Be Important |url=http://fortune.com/2017/10/31/qualcomm-chips-apple-iphone-ditch/ |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 31, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111041833/http://fortune.com/2017/10/31/qualcomm-chips-apple-iphone-ditch/ |archive-date=November 11, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Buy unlocked\">{{cite web |first=Sascha |last=Segan |title=Why You Should Buy an Unlocked or Verizon iPhone 8, iPhone X |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/news/91205/why-you-should-buy-an-unlocked-or-verizon-iphone-8-iphone-x |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=September 18, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201102132/http://uk.pcmag.com/news/91205/why-you-should-buy-an-unlocked-or-verizon-iphone-8-iphone-x |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Professional measurement tests performed by wireless signal testing firm ''Cellular Insights'' indicated that, as in the previous-gen [[iPhone 7#Performance differences|iPhone 7]], Qualcomm's chips outperform Intel's in LTE download speeds, up to 67% faster in very weak signal conditions,<ref>{{cite web |first=Joe |last=Rossignol |title=iPhone X Models With Qualcomm Modem Still Have Faster LTE Speeds Than Those With Intel Modems |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/12/01/qualcomm-iphone-x-still-faster-than-intel/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=December 1, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203203157/https://www.macrumors.com/2017/12/01/qualcomm-iphone-x-still-faster-than-intel/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Dziedzic |title=Every iPhone X is not created equal, new study says |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/not-all-iphone-xs-are-created-equal/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=December 1, 2017 |accessdate=December 4, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203051723/https://www.cnet.com/news/not-all-iphone-xs-are-created-equal/ |archive-date=December 3, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> resulting in some sources recommending the purchase of an unlocked iPhone X or one bought through cellular carrier [[Verizon Wireless|Verizon]], in order to get the models featuring the faster Qualcomm modem.<ref name=\"Buy unlocked\" /> Additionally, ''[[CNET]]'' reported in September 2017 that the new iPhone models, including X, [[iPhone 8|8 and 8 Plus]], do not have the ability to connect to the next-generation of [[LTE (telecommunication)|wireless LTE data connection]], despite 10 new [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices, including flagships from main smartphone competitor [[Samsung]], all having the capability to do so. While Apple's new smartphones have support for \"[[LTE Advanced]]\", with a theoretical peak speed of 500 [[megabit]]s per second, the Android models have the ability to connect to \"Gigabit LTE\", allowing theoretical speeds up to 1 [[gigabit]] per second, doubling Apple's speed.<ref>{{cite web |first=Roger |last=Cheng |title=Apple's iPhone X, iPhone 8 lack a feature the Galaxy S8 rocks |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apples-iphone-x-iphone-8-lack-one-feature-on-the-galaxy-s8/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=September 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 8, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208175058/https://www.cnet.com/news/apples-iphone-x-iphone-8-lack-one-feature-on-the-galaxy-s8/ |archive-date=December 8, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===NFC problems===\nAfter releasing the iPhone X in Japan and China, customers experienced issues related to the phone's [[Near-field communication|NFC]] while trying to access public transit [[contactless smart card|smart card readers]]. In April 2018, Apple released a revision to the iPhone X, that included a vastly improved NFC chip. This solved the problem of NFC reader errors in most cases. Previously around 1 out of 3 NFC attempts would fail after initial reports. This issue also affected users in America.<ref name=\"Breckinridge Bassett\"/>\n\n===Display Module Replacement Program===\nApple has determined an issue with certain iPhone X devices where the display wouldn't respond to the user's touch, due to an component that might fail on the display module. Apple stated that they will repair the affected devices, free of charge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.apple.com/iphone-x-display-module-replacement-program|title=iPhone X Display Module Replacement Program for Touch Issues - Apple Support|website=support.apple.com}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline of iPhone models==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of iOS devices]]\n* [[History of iPhone]]\n* [[Comparison of smartphones]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|lcfirst=yes}}\n* {{Official website|https://web.archive.org/web/20171202150033/https://www.apple.com/iphone/|iPhone X official site}} (archived)\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2017]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2017]]\n[[Category:Phones with multiple rear cameras]]\n[[Category:Discontinued smartphones]]\n", "name_user": "Apaesu", "label": "safe", "comment": "there was a random url at top of page", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_X"}
{"title_page": "South Island robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref>), and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.<ref name=\"ref13\"/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=\"ref1\"/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=\"ref6\"/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=\"ref8\">{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=\"ref6\"/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=\"ref11\"/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=\"ref12\">{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=\"ref11\"/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities.<ref name=\"ref9\"/> Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs<ref name=\"ref13\">{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=\"ref14\">{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=\"ref5\"/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=\"ref11\">{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=\"ref12\">{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=\"ref10\"/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion, however these are not cached.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=\"ref2\"/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=\"ref4\">{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=\"ref9\"/> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=\"ref8\"/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=\"ref16\">{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref>), and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.<ref name=\"ref13\"/>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=\"ref1\"/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=\"ref5\">{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=\"ref6\">{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=\"ref6\"/>  There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=\"IUCN\"/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=\"ref7\">{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=\"ref8\">{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=\"ref6\"/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=\"ref10\">{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=\"ref11\"/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=\"ref12\">{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=\"ref11\"/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities.<ref name=\"ref9\"/> Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs<ref name=\"ref13\">{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref> with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=\"ref14\">{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=\"ref2\"/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=\"ref5\"/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=\"ref11\">{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=\"ref11\">{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=\"ref10\"/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion, however these are not cached.<ref name=\"ref5\"/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=\"ref2\"/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=\"ref4\">{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=\"ref9\"/> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=\"ref8\"/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=\"ref16\">{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFeeding:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Island_robin"}
{"title_page": "Ivica Gvozden", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Ivica Gvozden\n|image               = \n|caption             = \n|fullname            = \n|birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1968|10|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = [[SFR Yugoslavia]]\n|height              = \n|position            = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n|currentclub         = \n|clubnumber          = \n|youthyears1         = \n|youthclubs1         = \n|years1              = 1986\u20131990\n|clubs1              = [[NK Iskra Bugojno|Iskra Bugojno]]\n|caps1               = 25\n|goals1              = 0\n|years2              = 1990\u20131993\n|clubs2              = [[FK Rad|Rad Beograd]]\n|caps2               = 61\n|goals2              = 0\n|years3              = 1994\u20131995\n|clubs3              = [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|caps3               = 4\n|goals3              = 0\n|years4              = 1996\u20131997\n|clubs4              = [[Chemnitzer FC]]\n|caps4               = 26\n|goals4              = 1\n|years5              = 1998\n|clubs5              = [[HNK \u0160ibenik|\u0160ibenik]]\n|caps5               = 14\n|goals5              = 0\n|years6              = 2001\u20132002\n|clubs6              = [[HNK Grude|Grude]]\n|caps6               = 27\n|goals6              = 0\n|nationalyears1      = \n|nationalteam1       = [[Croatia national futsal team|Croatia futsal]]\n|nationalcaps1       = \n|nationalgoals1      = \n}}\n\n'''Ivica Gvozden''' (born 14 October 1968) is a [[Croats|Croatian]] former [[Association football|football]] defender.  He later also became a professional [[futsal]] player.\n\n==Career==\nAfter playing with [[NK Iskra Bugojno]] in the [[Yugoslav Second League]] since 1986, in 1990 he moved to Belgrade and signed with [[Yugoslav First League]] club [[FK Rad]] where he played until 1993.<ref>playerhistory.com</ref>  In 1994, he moved to Croatia and joined [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb]], known as ''Croatia Zagreb'' back then.  In 1996, he moved to Germany where he played with [[Chemnitzer FC]]<ref>[http://www.chemnitzerfc.de/cfc/verein/geschichte/spieler/spieleransicht/profil/gvozden.html?cHash=92e69e4a2b379948f993a181152b5d31 Ivica Gvozden] at Chemnitzer FC official website</ref> one and a half seasons playing in the [[Regionalliga Nordost]].  During the winter break of the 1997\u201398 season, he returned to Croatia and signed with [[Prva HNL|1. HNL]] side [[HNK \u0160ibenik]].<ref>[http://hrnogomet.com/hnl/igrac.php?id=745&stranica=1 Ivica Gvozden] at hrnogomet.com</ref> He played with [[HNK Grude]] in the [[2001\u201302 Premier League of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>[http://forum.sportsport.ba/viewtopic.php?f=6&t=3114&start=40]</ref>\n\n==Futsal career==\nIvica Gvozden was part of the [[Croatia national futsal team]] at the [[2001 UEFA Futsal Championship]].<ref>[http://www.hns-cff.hr/?ln=en&w=statistike&repka=FS&id=51377 Ivica Gvozden] at HNS-cff.hr</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gvozden, Ivica}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Croatian footballers]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:FK Rad players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:HNK \u0160ibenik players]]\n[[Category:Croatian First Football League players]]\n[[Category:Chemnitzer FC players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Croatian men's futsal players]]\n\n\n{{Croatia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Ivica Gvozden\n|image               = \n|caption             = \n|fullname            = \n|birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1968|10|14|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = [[SFR Yugoslavia]]\n|height              = \n|position            = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n|currentclub         = \n|clubnumber          = \n|youthyears1         = \n|youthclubs1         = \n|years1              = 1986\u20131990\n|clubs1              = [[NK Iskra Bugojno|Iskra Bugojno]]\n|caps1               = 25\n|goals1              = 0\n|years2              = 1990\u20131993\n|clubs2              = [[FK Rad|Rad Beograd]]\n|caps2               = 61\n|goals2              = 0\n|years3              = 1994\u20131995\n|clubs3              = [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|caps3               = 4\n|goals3              = 0\n|years4              = 1996\u20131997\n|clubs4              = [[Chemnitzer FC]]\n|caps4               = 26\n|goals4              = 1\n|years5              = 1998\n|clubs5              = [[HNK \u0160ibenik]]\n|caps5               = 14\n|goals5              = 0\n|years6              = 2001\u20132002\n|clubs6              = [[HNK Grude]]\n|caps6               = 27\n|goals6              = 0\n|nationalyears1      = \n|nationalteam1       = \n|nationalcaps1       = \n|nationalgoals1      = \n}}\n\n'''Ivica Gvozden''' (born 14 October 1968) is a [[Croats|Croatian]] former [[Association football|football]] defender.  He later became a [[futsal]] player.\n\n==Career==\nAfter playing with [[NK Iskra Bugojno]] in the [[Yugoslav Second League]] since 1986, in 1990 he moved to Belgrade and signed with [[Yugoslav First League]] club [[FK Rad]] where he played until 1993.<ref>playerhistory.com</ref>  In 1994, he moved to Croatia and joined [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb]], known as ''Croatia Zagreb'' back then.  In 1996, he moved to Germany where he played with [[Chemnitzer FC]]<ref>[http://www.chemnitzerfc.de/cfc/verein/geschichte/spieler/spieleransicht/profil/gvozden.html?cHash=92e69e4a2b379948f993a181152b5d31 Ivica Gvozden] at Chemnitzer FC official website</ref> one and a half seasons playing in the [[Regionalliga Nordost]].  During the winter break of the 1997\u201398 season, he returned to Croatia and signed with [[Prva HNL|1. HNL]] side [[HNK \u0160ibenik]].<ref>[http://hrnogomet.com/hnl/igrac.php?id=745&stranica=1 Ivica Gvozden] at hrnogomet.com</ref> He played with [[HNK Grude]] in the [[2001\u201302 Premier League of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>[http://forum.sportsport.ba/viewtopic.php?f=6&t=3114&start=40]</ref>\n\n==Futsal career==\nIvica Gvozden was part of the [[Croatia national futsal team]] at the [[2001 UEFA Futsal Championship]].<ref>[http://www.hns-cff.hr/?ln=en&w=statistike&repka=FS&id=51377 Ivica Gvozden] at HNS-cff.hr</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gvozden, Ivica}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Croatian footballers]]\n[[Category:Croatian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:FK Rad players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:HNK \u0160ibenik players]]\n[[Category:Croatian First Football League players]]\n[[Category:Chemnitzer FC players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Croatian men's futsal players]]\n\n\n{{Croatia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "FkpCascais", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivica_Gvozden"}
{"title_page": "Bogdan Milovanov", "text_new": "{{short description|Ukrainian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Bogdan Milovanov\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| fullname = Bogdan Milovanov\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|4|19|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Lugansk]], Ukraine\n| height = 1.78m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right back]]\n| currentclub = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|Sporting B]]\n| clubnumber = 2\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[Alcobendas CF|Alcobendas]]\n| youthyears3 = 2015 | youthclubs3 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]]\n| years1 = 2015 | clubs1 = [[Alcobendas CF|Alcobendas]] | caps1 = 12 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs2 = [[Getafe CF B|Getafe B]] | caps2 = 15 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2017\u20132018 | clubs3 = [[UD San Sebasti\u00e1n de los Reyes|SS Reyes]] | caps3 = 22 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2018\u2013 | clubs4 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|Sporting B]] | caps4 = 40 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2019\u2013 | clubs5 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|Sporting Gij\u00f3n]] | caps5 = 4 | goals5 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2019\u2013 | nationalteam1 = [[Ukraine national under-21 football team|Ukraine U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 6 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update = 21:15, 14 January 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Bogdan Milovanov''' (born 19 April 1998) is a Ukrainian [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for Spanish club [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Lugansk]], Milovanov moved to the [[Community of Madrid]] at early age and made his senior debut with [[Alcobendas CF]] during the [[2014\u201315 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2014\u201315 season]], in [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]. In July 2015, he moved to [[Getafe CF]] and returned to youth football.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.intersoccermadrid.com/en/getafe-cf-signs-bogdan-milovanov-intersoccer-madrid-student/|title=Getafe C.F. signs Bogdan Milovanov, Intersoccer Madrid student|publisher=InterSoccer Madrid|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2017, after being sparingly used by [[Getafe CF B|Getafe's reserves]], Milovanov signed for [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] side [[UD San Sebasti\u00e1n de los Reyes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ud-sanse.com/2017/08/bogdan-nuevo-fichaje-de-la-u-d-sanse/|title=Bogdan, nuevo fichaje de la U.D.Sanse|trans-title=Bogdan, new signing of U.D. ''Sanse''|publisher=UD SS Reyes|language=es|date=10 August 2017|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> On 9 July of the following year, he joined another [[reserve team]], [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B]] also in the third division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realsporting.com/noticia/el-sporting-b-incorpora-a-bogdan-milovanov|title=El Sporting B incorpora a Bogdan Milovanov|trans-title=Sporting B sign Bogdan Milovanov|publisher=Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|language=es|date=9 July 2018|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nMilovanov made his debut for the [[Asturias|Asturians]]' [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|first team]] on 14 January 2020, starting in a 1\u20130 home win against [[Elche CF]] for the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/cronica/2020/01/14/5e1e0326e2704ec5148b45f5.html|title=Manu aparece al final y firma el primer triunfo de Djukic|trans-title=Manu shows up at the end and seals the first triumph of Djukic|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=14 January 2020|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|22218}}\n*{{LaPreferente|209217/bogdan}}\n*{{Soccerway|bogdan-milovanov/416201}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milovanov, Bogdan}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Getafe CF B players]]\n[[Category:UD San Sebasti\u00e1n de los Reyes players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ukrainian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Bogdan Milovanov\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| fullname = Bogdan Milovanov\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1998|4|19|df=y}} \n| birth_place = [[Lugansk]], Ukraine\n| height = 1.78m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right back]]\n| currentclub = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|Sporting B]]\n| clubnumber = 2\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[Alcobendas CF|Alcobendas]]\n| youthyears3 = 2015 | youthclubs3 = [[Getafe CF|Getafe]]\n| years1 = 2015 | clubs1 = [[Alcobendas CF|Alcobendas]] | caps1 = 12 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2015\u20132017 | clubs2 = [[Getafe CF B|Getafe B]] | caps2 = 15 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2017\u20132018 | clubs3 = [[UD San Sebasti\u00e1n de los Reyes|SS Reyes]] | caps3 = 22 | goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2018\u2013 | clubs4 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B|Sporting B]] | caps4 = 40 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 2019\u2013 | clubs5 = [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|Sporting Gij\u00f3n]] | caps5 = 4 | goals5 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2019\u2013 | nationalteam1 = [[Ukraine national under-21 football team|Ukraine U21]] | nationalcaps1 = 6 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update = 21:15, 14 January 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Bogdan Milovanov''' (born 19 April 1998) is an Ukrainian [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for Spanish club [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Lugansk]], Milovanov moved to the [[Community of Madrid]] at early age and made his senior debut with [[Alcobendas CF]] during the [[2014\u201315 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2014\u201315 season]], in [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]]. In July 2015, he moved to [[Getafe CF]] and returned to youth football.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.intersoccermadrid.com/en/getafe-cf-signs-bogdan-milovanov-intersoccer-madrid-student/|title=Getafe C.F. signs Bogdan Milovanov, Intersoccer Madrid student|publisher=InterSoccer Madrid|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 August 2017, after being sparingly used by [[Getafe CF B|Getafe's reserves]], Milovanov signed for [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] side [[UD San Sebasti\u00e1n de los Reyes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ud-sanse.com/2017/08/bogdan-nuevo-fichaje-de-la-u-d-sanse/|title=Bogdan, nuevo fichaje de la U.D.Sanse|trans-title=Bogdan, new signing of U.D. ''Sanse''|publisher=UD SS Reyes|language=es|date=10 August 2017|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> On 9 July of the following year, he joined another [[reserve team]], [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B]] also in the third division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realsporting.com/noticia/el-sporting-b-incorpora-a-bogdan-milovanov|title=El Sporting B incorpora a Bogdan Milovanov|trans-title=Sporting B sign Bogdan Milovanov|publisher=Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|language=es|date=9 July 2018|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nMilovanov made his debut for the [[Asturias|Asturians]]' [[Sporting de Gij\u00f3n|first team]] on 14 January 2020, starting in a 1\u20130 home win against [[Elche CF]] for the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/cronica/2020/01/14/5e1e0326e2704ec5148b45f5.html|title=Manu aparece al final y firma el primer triunfo de Djukic|trans-title=Manu shows up at the end and seals the first triumph of Djukic|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=14 January 2020|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|22218}}\n*{{LaPreferente|209217/bogdan}}\n*{{Soccerway|bogdan-milovanov/416201}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milovanov, Bogdan}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Getafe CF B players]]\n[[Category:UD San Sebasti\u00e1n de los Reyes players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Sporting de Gij\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: an Ukrainian \u2192 a Ukrainian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bogdan_Milovanov"}
{"title_page": "Mykola Riabovil", "text_new": "'''Mykola Riabovil''' (born 17 December 1883, in the village of Dinsk, the Kuban Region, the Russian Empire - died 13 June 1919, at [[Rostov-on-Don]], All-Large Army Donskoy) was a Ukrainian political figure in the [[Kuban]]. During the [[Russian Civil War]] he was the chairman of the [[Kuban Legislative Council]] and the chairman of the [[Kuban Military Council]].<ref>https://enigma.ua/articles/kubanska_narodna_respublika</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riabovil, Mykola}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian politicians]]\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Mykola Riabovil''' (born 17 December 1883, in the village of Dinsk, the Kuban Region, the Russian Empire - died 13 June 1919, at [[Rostov-on-Don]], All-Large Army Donskoy) was an Ukrainian political figure in the [[Kuban]]. During the [[Russian Civil War]] he was the chairman of the [[Kuban Legislative Council]] and the chairman of the [[Kuban Military Council]].<ref>https://enigma.ua/articles/kubanska_narodna_respublika</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riabovil, Mykola}}\n[[Category:Ukrainian politicians]]\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: an Ukrainian \u2192 a Ukrainian", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mykola_Riabovil"}
{"title_page": "Treacle mining", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n[[File:Treacle Mine pub Essex.jpg|thumb|upright|The Treacle Mine public house in [[Thurrock]], Essex.]]\n'''Treacle mining''' is the fictitious mining of [[treacle]] (similar to [[molasses]]) in a raw form similar to coal. The subject purports to be serious but is an attempt to test [[credulity]]. Thick black treacle makes the deception plausible. The topic has been a joke in [[British humour]] since the mid-19th century.\n\n==Origins==\nOne possible origin of the joke is from 1853 when 8,000 [[British Army]] soldiers were camped on [[Chobham Common]]. The camp included storehouses containing barrels. When the soldiers left for the [[Crimean War]] and the site was dismantled, they buried barrels to avoid having to remove them. Some of the barrels contained treacle and [[Chobham]] villagers who discovered and removed them were called \"treacle miners\" as a joke. Local folklore about treacle mining was extended into history back to [[Roman Britain]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Alice Eats Wonderland|page=53|author1=August Imholtz  |author2=Alison Tannenbaum |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=Applewood Books|year=2009|isbn=978-1429091060}}</ref>\n\nAnother explanation is that \"treacle\" meant 'a medicine', derived from the appearance of the Greek derivative '[[theriac]]al' meaning medicinal (Greek ''theriake'' \"curative\", \"antidote\"), so the various healing wells around Britain were called \"treacle wells\". Treacle later came to mean a sticky syrup after the popularity of a honey-based drug called \"[[Venice treacle]]\", and the continued use of the old form in the treacle wells led to the joke.<ref>{{Cite book |author1       = Cooper, Quentin\n |author2       = Sullivan, Paul\n |lastauthoramp = yes\n |title         = Maypoles, Martyrs and Mayhem\n |publisher     = Bloomsbury\n |year          = 1994\n |isbn          = 0-7475-1807-6\n |page          = \n |url-access    = registration\n |url           = https://archive.org/details/maypolesmartyrsm0000coop\n}}{{Page needed|date=January 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hematite micaceous.jpg|thumb|Micaceous hematite, a possible source for some treacle mine stories.]]\nIn Devon, on the eastern edge of [[Dartmoor]], UK, the remains of mines that produced [[micaceous hematite]], used as [[pounce (calligraphy)|pounce]] to dust early ink to prevent smearing, are known locally as \"treacle mines\" since they show a glistening black residue that looks like treacle.\n\n==Locations==\nThe village of [[Sabden]] in [[Lancashire]] cultivated a considerable body of folklore about local treacle mining in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lancashire mill town traditions|page=9|author=William Reginald Mitchell|publisher=Dalesman|year=1977|isbn=0852064144}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Lancashire nicknames and sayings|page=63|author=Bob Dobson|publisher=Dalesman|year=1973|isbn=0852061773}}</ref> The local newspaper helped foster the myth, publishing numerous stories about the fictitious mines.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Lore of the Land: A Guide to England's Legends, from Spring-heeled Jack to the Witches of Warboys|page=871|author1=Jennifer Westwood  |author2=Jacqueline Simpson |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=Penguin Books|year=2005|isbn=0141021039}}</ref>\n\nThe paper mills around [[Maidstone]] in Kent were known  as \"The [[Tovil]] Treacle Mines\"<ref>Tovil pronounced to rhyme with \"[[Bovril]]\" \u2013 not \"Toeville\")</ref> by locals, after the area where one of the mills owned by Albert E. Reed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reed-elsevier.com/index.cfm?articleid=113|title=Reed Elsevier \u2013 Product highlight|publisher=[[Reed Elsevier]]|accessdate=31 January 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212122102/http://www.reed-elsevier.com/index.cfm?articleid=113|archivedate=12 December 2004}}</ref> was situated. The company helped the myth with a float in Maidstone carnival with a \"treacle mine\" theme. \n\nOne suggested source of the story in this area is a rumour that the paper industry was threatened during the [[Second World War]] because there was no imported [[timber]]. Fermentation of straw was tried, creating a sticky goo. There were attempts to make paper from other than rags in the 19th century and an early commercial success was achieved by Samuel Hook and his son, Charles Townsend Hook, using straw at Upper Tovil Mill in the 1850s. The road next to Upper Tovil Mill became known, and was later named, as Straw Mill Hill. To produce pulp, the straw was cooked in hot alkali. After separation of the fibre, the remaining liquid looked like black treacle. Upper Tovil Mill closed in the 1980s and the site was used for a housing estate.\n\n[[Tudeley]] and [[Frittenden]] in Kent are also said to have had treacle mines. A tank wagon on the [[Kent and East Sussex Railway]] was painted in sham \"Frittenden Treacle Mines\" livery in 2009.<ref name=Tank>{{cite web|url=https://www.kesr.org.uk/visitor-information/about-kesr/stations/15-stock/wagons/128-132|title=N\u00ba. 132 \u2013 Esso 14 ton Tank Wagon N\u00ba. 2338|publisher=Kent & East Sussex Railway|accessdate=23 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218134931/https://www.kesr.org.uk/visitor-information/about-kesr/stations/15-stock/wagons/128-132|archivedate=18 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSuggestions of a treacle mine in [[Buxted]] were published by the \"Friends of Horwich\".<ref>[http://www.treacleminer.com/docs/buxtedtreacle.htm Buxted Treacle Mine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717093624/http://www.treacleminer.com/docs/buxtedtreacle.htm |date=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[Tadley]] treacle mines had a local hotel named after them and a Tadley Treacle Fair is held. Legend says the name derives from using treacle tins to store money because banks could not be trusted. The tins were buried around the village. Criminals mined for tins.\n\n[[Hemel Hempstead]] in [[Hertfordshire]] has a legend of having a treacle mine and a local nickname since around [[World War One]] was \"Treacle Bumstead\".<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Boy from Treacle Bumstead: A Country Lad's Journey from Reform School to National Service|last = Sears|first = Ken|publisher = Simon & Schuster Ltd|year = 2013|isbn = 978-1471113574|location = |pages = }}</ref> [[Wareside]], also in Hertfordshire, has long had its own \"treacle mines\". When asked \"where have you been?\", it was often a popular answer in and around [[Ware, Hertfordshire|Ware]], to say \"down the treacle mines!\"\n\nTreacle mines have also been claimed in the twin villages [[Trimley St. Martin]] and [[Trimley St. Mary]] (Suffolk), [[Wem]] ([[Shropshire]]), [[Talskiddy]], [[Bisham]], [[Nuneaton]], [[Sway, Hampshire|Sway]] ([[Hampshire]]), [[West Ginge|Ginge]] ([[Oxfordshire]]), [[Chobham]] ([[Surrey]]), [[Tongham]], [[Tadley]], [[Skidby]], [[Ditchford railway station|Ditchford]], [[Crick, Northamptonshire|Crick]] ([[Northamptonshire]]), [[Saddington]] ([[Leicestershire]]), [[Dunchideock]] and many other locations across [[Somerset]] and [[Devon]],<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Barber\n| first = Chips\n| title = Around & About the Haldon Hills\n| publisher = Obelisk Publications\n| year = 1982\n| pages = 95\u201397\n| isbn = 0-946651-14-0}}</ref> in several northern towns including [[Natland]] and [[Baggrow]] in [[Cumbria]] and [[Pudsey]] in Yorkshire,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treacleminer.com/Mines/Pudsey.html|title=Pudsey|website=All Things Treacle|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> in [[Croftamie]], Scotland, and in the fictional village of Wymsey.\n\n==Actual places==\nSeveral [[public house]]s, restaurants and hotels have borne the name. The Treacle Mine public house in [[Grays, Essex|Grays]], [[Thurrock]], Essex (pictured above) is an example, and the adjacent [[Treacle Mine Roundabout]], which features on the local bus timetable, is named after the public house.\n\nThere is a restaurant/pub named Treacle Mine in [[Polegate]], East Sussex;.<ref>{{cite web|last=Table Table|title=Treacle Mine Restaurant|url=http://www.tabletable.co.uk/content/tabletable/our-pubs/brighton/treacle-mine.html|publisher=Whitbread plc|accessdate=30 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003223837/http://www.tabletable.co.uk/content/tabletable/our-pubs/brighton/treacle-mine.html|archivedate=3 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The name refers to the Polegate treacle mines, a long-running tale in the area that is very popular, with locals dressing as treacle miners for the 1978 Eastbourne carnival.  The origins are believed to be associated with a nearby sweet factory.<ref>https://www.whitbreadinns.co.uk/treacle-mine-pub-and-restaurant/story retrieved 1 May 2017</ref>\n\nThe Broomsquire Hotel in [[Tadley]], Hampshire, was previously the Treacle Mine Hotel; and another Treacle Mine pub is in [[Hereford]].\n\nSince April 2009 the town of [[Wincanton]] in Somerset, twinned with [[Ankh-Morpork]], has had a Treacle Mine Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7984118.stm|title=Roads named after Discworld books|publisher=BBC News|date=5 April 2009|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== Cultural references ==\nThe Treacle Mine has been a joke played on children and the gullible since at least the nineteenth century.\n*[[Ottershaw School]] in [[Surrey]] (a state boarding school founded in 1948 and closed in 1980) encouraged all new boys, on their first Sunday, to wait outside the Main gate for the coach that would take them on an outing to the Chobham Treacle Mines.\n*In ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' (1865) by [[Lewis Carroll]], Alice is shushed at the [[The Hatter|Mad Hatter's]] tea party for disbelieving a story told by the [[Dormouse]] about a treacle well, inspired by the [[holy well]] at [[Binsey, Oxfordshire]].\n*In ''[[Uncle and the Treacle Trouble]]'' (1967), a children's book by [[J. P. Martin]], the main character (an elephant named \"Uncle\") discovers the true meaning of a cryptic sign which reads \"Treac Levat\"; the characters soon discover that it relates to a vast hidden treacle vat.\n*Treacle mining features in several novels by [[Terry Pratchett]]. On the fictional [[Discworld (world)|Discworld]] treacle is mined from buried deposits of compressed ancient sugarcane. In the city of [[Ankh-Morpork]] there is a street named Treacle Mine Road, with the current watch house (analogous to a police station) found in the building formerly housing the entrance to a treacle mine. The books also make references to \"deep treacle\" deposits beneath the city. As with many features of the Discworld, treacle mines exist ''because'' people believe in them, according to the Discworld's Theory of Narrative Causality.\n*''[[The Treacle People]]'' was a children's TV show from 1995 based around the treacle mines of [[Sabden]] in [[Lancashire]].\n*All the members of the Seven Champions [[Molly dance|Molly Dancers]] <ref name=SevenChamps>[http://www.sevenchampions.org.uk Seven Champions Molly Dancers]</ref> from [[Kent]] are reputed to be treacle miners.\n*Some of [[Ken Dodd]]'s [[Diddy Men]] were said to work in a [[Jam sandwich (food)|jam butty]] mine.  This appears to be a similar concept.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cow tipping]]\n* [[Drop bear]]\n* [[Jackalope]]\n* [[Snipe hunt]]\n* [[Spaghetti tree]]\n* [[Wild haggis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.wymsey.co.uk/wymsey/treacle.htm Wymsey Treacle Mine]\n* [http://www.treacleminer.com Treacleminer \u2013 for all things treacle]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treacle Mining}}\n[[Category:British humour]]\n[[Category:Running gags]]\n[[Category:Fictional activities]]\n[[Category:Mining in fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n[[File:Treacle Mine pub Essex.jpg|thumb|upright|The Treacle Mine public house in [[Thurrock]], Essex.]]\n'''Treacle mining''' is the fictitious mining of [[treacle]] (similar to [[molasses]]) in a raw form similar to coal. The subject purports to be serious but is an attempt to test [[credulity]]. Thick black treacle makes the deception plausible. The topic has been a joke in [[British humour]] since the mid-19th century.\n\n==Origins==\nOne possible origin of the joke is from 1853 when 8,000 [[British Army]] soldiers were camped on [[Chobham Common]]. The camp included storehouses containing barrels. When the soldiers left for the [[Crimean War]] and the site was dismantled, they buried barrels to avoid having to remove them. Some of the barrels contained treacle and [[Chobham]] villagers who discovered and removed them were called \"treacle miners\" as a joke. Local folklore about treacle mining was extended into history back to [[Roman Britain]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Alice Eats Wonderland|page=53|author1=August Imholtz  |author2=Alison Tannenbaum |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=Applewood Books|year=2009|isbn=978-1429091060}}</ref>\n\nAnother explanation is that \"treacle\" meant 'a medicine', derived from the appearance of the Greek derivative '[[theriac]]al' meaning medicinal (Greek ''theriake'' \"curative\", \"antidote\"), so the various healing wells around Britain were called \"treacle wells\". Treacle later came to mean a sticky syrup after the popularity of a honey-based drug called \"[[Venice treacle]]\", and the continued use of the old form in the treacle wells led to the joke.<ref>{{Cite book |author1       = Cooper, Quentin\n |author2       = Sullivan, Paul\n |lastauthoramp = yes\n |title         = Maypoles, Martyrs and Mayhem\n |publisher     = Bloomsbury\n |year          = 1994\n |isbn          = 0-7475-1807-6\n |page          = \n |url-access    = registration\n |url           = https://archive.org/details/maypolesmartyrsm0000coop\n}}{{Page needed|date=January 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hematite micaceous.jpg|thumb|Micaceous hematite, a possible source for some treacle mine stories.]]\nIn Devon, on the eastern edge of [[Dartmoor]], UK, the remains of mines that produced [[micaceous hematite]], used as [[pounce (calligraphy)|pounce]] to dust early ink to prevent smearing, are known locally as \"treacle mines\" since they show a glistening black residue that looks like treacle.\n\n==Locations==\nThe village of [[Sabden]] in [[Lancashire]] cultivated a considerable body of folklore about local treacle mining in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite book|title=Lancashire mill town traditions|page=9|author=William Reginald Mitchell|publisher=Dalesman|year=1977|isbn=0852064144}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Lancashire nicknames and sayings|page=63|author=Bob Dobson|publisher=Dalesman|year=1973|isbn=0852061773}}</ref> The local newspaper helped foster the myth, publishing numerous stories about the fictitious mines.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Lore of the Land: A Guide to England's Legends, from Spring-heeled Jack to the Witches of Warboys|page=871|author1=Jennifer Westwood  |author2=Jacqueline Simpson |lastauthoramp=yes |publisher=Penguin Books|year=2005|isbn=0141021039}}</ref>\n\nThe paper mills around [[Maidstone]] in Kent were known  as \"The [[Tovil]] Treacle Mines\"<ref>Tovil pronounced to rhyme with \"[[Bovril]]\" \u2013 not \"Toeville\")</ref> by locals, after the area where one of the mills owned by Albert E. Reed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reed-elsevier.com/index.cfm?articleid=113|title=Reed Elsevier \u2013 Product highlight|publisher=[[Reed Elsevier]]|accessdate=31 January 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041212122102/http://www.reed-elsevier.com/index.cfm?articleid=113|archivedate=12 December 2004}}</ref> was situated. The company helped the myth with a float in Maidstone carnival with a \"treacle mine\" theme. \n\nOne suggested source of the story in this area is a rumour that the paper industry was threatened during the [[Second World War]] because there was no imported [[timber]]. Fermentation of straw was tried, creating a sticky goo. There were attempts to make paper from other than rags in the 19th century and an early commercial success was achieved by Samuel Hook and his son, Charles Townsend Hook, using straw at Upper Tovil Mill in the 1850s. The road next to Upper Tovil Mill became known, and was later named, as Straw Mill Hill. To produce pulp, the straw was cooked in hot alkali. After separation of the fibre, the remaining liquid looked like black treacle. Upper Tovil Mill closed in the 1980s and the site was used for a housing estate.\n\n[[Tudeley]] and [[Frittenden]] in Kent are also said to have had treacle mines. A tank wagon on the [[Kent and East Sussex Railway]] was painted in sham \"Frittenden Treacle Mines\" livery in 2009.<ref name=Tank>{{cite web|url=https://www.kesr.org.uk/visitor-information/about-kesr/stations/15-stock/wagons/128-132|title=N\u00ba. 132 \u2013 Esso 14 ton Tank Wagon N\u00ba. 2338|publisher=Kent & East Sussex Railway|accessdate=23 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131218134931/https://www.kesr.org.uk/visitor-information/about-kesr/stations/15-stock/wagons/128-132|archivedate=18 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSuggestions of a treacle mine in [[Buxted]] were published by the \"Friends of Horwich\".<ref>[http://www.treacleminer.com/docs/buxtedtreacle.htm Buxted Treacle Mine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717093624/http://www.treacleminer.com/docs/buxtedtreacle.htm |date=17 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n[[Tadley]] treacle mines had a local hotel named after them and a Tadley Treacle Fair is held. Legend says the name derives from using treacle tins to store money because banks could not be trusted. The tins were buried around the village. Criminals mined for tins.\n\n[[Hemel Hempstead]] in [[Hertfordshire]] has a legend of having a treacle mine and a local nickname since around [[World War One]] was \"Treacle Bumstead\".<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Boy from Treacle Bumstead: A Country Lad's Journey from Reform School to National Service|last = Sears|first = Ken|publisher = Simon & Schuster Ltd|year = 2013|isbn = 978-1471113574|location = |pages = }}</ref> [[Wareside]], also in Hertfordshire, has long had its own \"treacle mines\". When asked \"where have you been?\", it was often a popular answer in and around [[Ware, Hertfordshire|Ware]], to say \"down the treacle mines!\"\n\nTreacle mines have also been claimed in the twin villages [[Trimley St. Martin]] and [[Trimley St. Mary]] (Suffolk), [[Wem]] ([[Shropshire]]), [[Talskiddy]], [[Bisham]], [[Nuneaton]], [[Sway, Hampshire|Sway]] ([[Hampshire]]), [[West Ginge|Ginge]] ([[Oxfordshire]]), [[Chobham]] ([[Surrey]]), [[Tongham]], [[Tadley]], [[Skidby]], [[Ditchford railway station|Ditchford]], [[Crick, Northamptonshire|Crick]] ([[Northamptonshire]]), [[Saddington]] ([[Leicestershire]]), [[Dunchideock]] and many other locations across [[Somerset]] and [[Devon]],<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Barber\n| first = Chips\n| title = Around & About the Haldon Hills\n| publisher = Obelisk Publications\n| year = 1982\n| pages = 95\u201397\n| isbn = 0-946651-14-0}}</ref> in several northern towns including [[Natland]] and [[Baggrow]] in [[Cumbria]] and [[Pudsey]] in Yorkshire,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treacleminer.com/Mines/Pudsey.html|title=Pudsey|website=All Things Treacle|accessdate=17 November 2017}}</ref> in [[Croftamie]], Scotland, and in the fictional village of Wymsey.\n\n==Actual places==\nSeveral [[public house]]s, restaurants and hotels have borne the name. The Treacle Mine public house in [[Grays]], [[Thurrock]], Essex (pictured above) is an example, and the adjacent [[Treacle Mine Roundabout]], which features on the local bus timetable, is named after the public house.\n\nThere is a restaurant/pub named Treacle Mine in [[Polegate]], East Sussex;.<ref>{{cite web|last=Table Table|title=Treacle Mine Restaurant|url=http://www.tabletable.co.uk/content/tabletable/our-pubs/brighton/treacle-mine.html|publisher=Whitbread plc|accessdate=30 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003223837/http://www.tabletable.co.uk/content/tabletable/our-pubs/brighton/treacle-mine.html|archivedate=3 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  The name refers to the Polegate treacle mines, a long-running tale in the area that is very popular, with locals dressing as treacle miners for the 1978 Eastbourne carnival.  The origins are believed to be associated with a nearby sweet factory.<ref>https://www.whitbreadinns.co.uk/treacle-mine-pub-and-restaurant/story retrieved 1 May 2017</ref>\n\nThe Broomsquire Hotel in [[Tadley]], Hampshire, was previously the Treacle Mine Hotel; and another Treacle Mine pub is in [[Hereford]].\n\nSince April 2009 the town of [[Wincanton]] in Somerset, twinned with [[Ankh-Morpork]], has had a Treacle Mine Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/somerset/7984118.stm|title=Roads named after Discworld books|publisher=BBC News|date=5 April 2009|accessdate=2011-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== Cultural references ==\nThe Treacle Mine has been a joke played on children and the gullible since at least the nineteenth century.\n*[[Ottershaw School]] in [[Surrey]] (a state boarding school founded in 1948 and closed in 1980) encouraged all new boys, on their first Sunday, to wait outside the Main gate for the coach that would take them on an outing to the Chobham Treacle Mines.\n*In ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' (1865) by [[Lewis Carroll]], Alice is shushed at the [[The Hatter|Mad Hatter's]] tea party for disbelieving a story told by the [[Dormouse]] about a treacle well, inspired by the [[holy well]] at [[Binsey, Oxfordshire]].\n*In ''[[Uncle and the Treacle Trouble]]'' (1967), a children's book by [[J. P. Martin]], the main character (an elephant named \"Uncle\") discovers the true meaning of a cryptic sign which reads \"Treac Levat\"; the characters soon discover that it relates to a vast hidden treacle vat.\n*Treacle mining features in several novels by [[Terry Pratchett]]. On the fictional [[Discworld (world)|Discworld]] treacle is mined from buried deposits of compressed ancient sugarcane. In the city of [[Ankh-Morpork]] there is a street named Treacle Mine Road, with the current watch house (analogous to a police station) found in the building formerly housing the entrance to a treacle mine. The books also make references to \"deep treacle\" deposits beneath the city. As with many features of the Discworld, treacle mines exist ''because'' people believe in them, according to the Discworld's Theory of Narrative Causality.\n*''[[The Treacle People]]'' was a children's TV show from 1995 based around the treacle mines of [[Sabden]] in [[Lancashire]].\n*All the members of the Seven Champions [[Molly dance|Molly Dancers]] <ref name=SevenChamps>[http://www.sevenchampions.org.uk Seven Champions Molly Dancers]</ref> from [[Kent]] are reputed to be treacle miners.\n*Some of [[Ken Dodd]]'s [[Diddy Men]] were said to work in a [[Jam sandwich (food)|jam butty]] mine.  This appears to be a similar concept.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cow tipping]]\n* [[Drop bear]]\n* [[Jackalope]]\n* [[Snipe hunt]]\n* [[Spaghetti tree]]\n* [[Wild haggis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.wymsey.co.uk/wymsey/treacle.htm Wymsey Treacle Mine]\n* [http://www.treacleminer.com Treacleminer \u2013 for all things treacle]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treacle Mining}}\n[[Category:British humour]]\n[[Category:Running gags]]\n[[Category:Fictional activities]]\n[[Category:Mining in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrays(link changed toGrays, Essex) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treacle_mining"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Cuomo", "text_new": "{{short description|56th Governor of New York}}\n{{pp-semi-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Andrew Cuomo\n| image        = Andrew Cuomo by Pat Arnow cropped.jpeg\n| order        = 56th\n| office       = Governor of New York\n| lieutenant   = [[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]]<br>[[Kathy Hochul]]\n| term_start   = January 1, 2011\n| term_end     =\n| predecessor  = [[David Paterson]]\n| successor    =\n| order2       = 64th\n| office2      = Attorney General of New York\n| governor2    = [[Eliot Spitzer]] <br> [[David Paterson]]\n| term_start2  = January 1, 2007\n| term_end2    = December 31, 2010\n| predecessor2 = [[Eliot Spitzer]]\n| successor2   = [[Eric Schneiderman]]\n| office3      = 11th [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]]\n| president3   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n| term_start3  = January 29, 1997\n| term_end3    = January 20, 2001\n| predecessor3 = [[Henry Cisneros]]\n| successor3   = [[Mel Mart\u00ednez]]\n| office4      = [[Department of Housing and Urban Development|Assistant Secretary of Housing and Urban Development for Community Planning and Development]]\n| president4   = Bill Clinton\n| term_start4  = May 28, 1993\n| term_end4    = January 29, 1997\n| predecessor4 = Skirma Kondratas\n| successor4   = [[Saul N. Ramirez Jr.|Saul Ramirez, Jr.]]\n| birth_name   = Andrew Mark Cuomo\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1957|12|6}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Kerry Kennedy]]|1990|2005|end=div}}\n| partner      = [[Sandra Lee (chef)|Sandra Lee]] (2005\u20132019)\n| children     = 3\n| parents      = [[Mario Cuomo]] <br> [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda Raffa]]\n| relatives    = [[Chris Cuomo]] (brother) <br> [[Margaret Cuomo]] (sister)\n| residence    = [[New York State Executive Mansion|Executive Mansion]]\n| education    = [[Fordham University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]]) <br> [[Albany Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| website      = {{url|governor.ny.gov|Government website}}\n| signature=Andrew_Cuomo_Signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Mark Cuomo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|w|o\u028a|m|o\u028a}} {{respell|KWOH|moh}}; born December 6, 1957) is an American politician, author, and lawyer serving since 2011 as the [[List of Governors of New York|56th]] [[governor of New York]]. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he was elected to the same position his late father, [[Mario Cuomo]], held for three terms.\n\nBorn in [[New York City]], Cuomo is a graduate of [[Fordham University]] and [[Albany Law School]] of [[Union University (New York)|Union University, New York]]. He began his career working as the campaign manager for his father, then as an assistant district attorney in New York City before entering private law practice. He founded Housing Enterprise for the Less Privileged (HELP USA) and was appointed chair of the New York City Homeless Commission, a position he held from 1990 to 1993.\n\nIn 1993, Cuomo joined the [[Presidency of Bill Clinton|Clinton Administration]] as Assistant Secretary for Community Planning and Development in the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]]. From 1997 to 2001, he served as the [[United States Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|U.S. Secretary of Housing and Urban Development]].\n\nIn [[2006 New York Attorney General election|2006]], Cuomo was elected [[New York State Attorney General|Attorney General of New York]]. He won the election as [[Governor of New York]] in [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|2010]] and has been reelected twice after winning primaries against liberal challengers [[Zephyr Teachout]] ([[2014 New York gubernatorial election|2014]]) and [[Cynthia Nixon]] ([[2018 New York gubernatorial election|2018]]). During his governorship, Cuomo oversaw the passage of a law legalizing [[Same-sex marriage in New York|same-sex marriage]] in New York; creation of the United States Climate Alliance, a group of states committed to fighting [[climate change]] by following the terms of the Paris Climate Accords; passage of the strictest [[NY SAFE Act|gun control]] law in the U.S.; [[Affordable Care Act|Medicaid expansion]]; a new tax code that raised taxes for the wealthy and lowered taxes for the middle class; paid family leave; an increase in the minimum wage; wage equality; and legislation legalizing medical marijuana.\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCuomo was born in the [[Queens]] borough of [[New York City]],<ref name=\"biography.com\">{{cite web| url = http://www.biography.com/people/andrew-cuomo-21024931 | title=Andrew Cuomo Biography: Government Official, Lawyer (1957\u2013)| publisher= [[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV channel)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) | accessdate= May 25, 2015}}</ref> the elder son of five children born to lawyer and later governor of New York, [[Mario Cuomo]] and [[Matilda Cuomo|Matilda]] (''n\u00e9e'' Raffa).<ref name=\"NYmag021389\">{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Blauner|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=--cCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35|title=All Star Family Feud: The Governor's In-Laws Battle Over a Father's Legacy|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=February 13, 1989|accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref> His parents were both of [[Italian-American|Italian]] descent; his paternal grandparents were from [[Nocera Inferiore]] and [[Tramonti, Campania|Tramonti]] in the [[Campania]] region of southern Italy, while his maternal grandparents were from [[Sicily]] (his grandfather from [[Messina]]).<ref name=\"NYmag021389\" /><ref name=Newsday10201988>{{cite news| first =Michael| last =Arena | author2 =Marianne Arneberg |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/newsday/access/104068528.html?dids=104068528:104068528&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+20%2C+1988&author=By+Michael+Arena+and+Marianne+Arneberg&pub=Newsday+(Combined+editions)&desc=Cuomo's+Father-in-Law+Dies&pqatl=google|title=Cuomo's Father-in-Law Dies|work=[[Newsday]]|date=October 20, 1988|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref> His younger brother, [[Chris Cuomo]], is a [[CNN]] journalist. His elder sister is noted radiologist [[Margaret Cuomo]].<ref name=\"NYTimes112310\">{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Barbaro|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/nyregion/24sexiest.html|title=All That Time Serving the Public? Very Sexy|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 23, 2010|accessdate=December 6, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101125130807/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/nyregion/24sexiest.html| archivedate= November 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from St. Gerard Majella's School in 1971<ref>Campanile, Carl. \"[https://nypost.com/2015/05/13/cuomo-and-cardinal-dolan-tout-parochial-school-tax-break/ Cuomo and Cardinal Dolan tout parochial school tax break],\" ''New York Post'', May 13, 2015.</ref> and [[Archbishop Molloy High School]] in 1975.<ref name=\"biography.com\" /> He received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] from [[Fordham University]] in 1979, and a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Albany Law School]] in 1982.<ref name=\"biography.com\"/>\n\n== Early career ==\nDuring his father's [[New York gubernatorial election, 1982|1982 campaign for Governor]], Cuomo was campaign manager, and then joined the governor's staff as one of his father's policy advisors and sometime Albany roommate,<ref name=NYm>Smith, Chris. \"[https://nymag.com/news/features/andrew-cuomo-2013-4/ The Albany Machiavelli],\" New York, April 14, 2013.</ref> earning $1 a year.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews092709\">{{cite news |first=Patrice|last=O'Shaughnessy|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/2009/09/27/2009-09-27_andrew_cuomo_from_horror_on_the_hudson_to_democrats_chosen_son.html |title=Andrew Cuomo: From Horror on the Hudson to Democrats' chosen son|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|location=New York |date=September 27, 2009|accessdate=December 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1984 to 1985, Cuomo was a New York assistant district attorney, and briefly worked at the law firm of Blutrich, Falcone & Miller. He founded Housing Enterprise for the Less Privileged (HELP) in 1986 and left his law firm to run HELP full-time in 1988.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews092709\" /> From 1990 to 1993, during the administration of [[Mayor of New York City|New York City mayor]], [[David Dinkins]], Cuomo was chair of the New York City Homeless Commission, which was charged with developing policies to address the homeless issue in the city and developing more housing options.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Secretary of HUD ==\n[[File:HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Cuomo as HUD Secretary]]\nAndrew Cuomo was appointed to the [[Department of Housing and Urban Development]] as Assistant Secretary for Community Planning and Development in 1993, a member of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s administration.<ref name=\"HUD\" /> After the departure of Secretary [[Henry Cisneros]] at the end of Clinton's first term under the cloud of an FBI investigation,<ref name=\"evans\">{{cite news | last =Evans | first =Judith | title =HUD's Cisneros to Leave a Legacy of Public Housing Reform | work =[[The Washington Post]] | page =E01 | date =November 30, 1996 | url =https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/cisneros/stories/cis113096.htm | accessdate =January 12, 2011 }}</ref> Cuomo was unanimously confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] to succeed him as [[Secretary of HUD]]. Cuomo served as Secretary from January 1997 until the Clinton administration ended in 2001.<ref name=\"HUD\" />\n\nIn 2000, Cuomo led HUD efforts to negotiate an agreement with the United States' largest handgun manufacturer, [[Smith & Wesson]], that required Smith & Wesson to change the design, distribution and marketing of guns to make them safer and to help keep them out of the hands of children and criminals.<ref name=\"HUD\">{{cite web|url=http://archives.hud.gov/secretaries/cuomobio.cfm |title=Andrew M. Cuomo |publisher=Archives, U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development |accessdate=May 20, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100527090837/http://archives.hud.gov/secretaries/cuomobio.cfm| archivedate= May 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Budgets enacted during his term contained initiatives to increase the supply of affordable housing and home ownership, and to create jobs and economic development. These included new rental assistance subsidies, reforms to integrate public housing, higher limits on mortgages insured by the [[Federal Housing Administration]], a crackdown on housing discrimination, expanded programs to help homeless people get housing and jobs, and creation of new [[Empowerment Zone|empowerment zone]]s.\n\n[[File:CuomoSummers.jpg|thumb|upright|Cuomo as HUD Secretary holding a press conference with then Treasury Secretary [[Larry Summers]]]]\nDuring Cuomo's tenure as HUD Secretary, he called for an increase in home ownership.<ref name=\"Fairbanks\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article50994.ece |title=Cuomo's HUD career under scrutiny |work=[[The Buffalo News]] |date=August 21, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010|first=Phil|last=Fairbanks| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100825154017/http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article50994.ece| archivedate= August 25, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> He also pushed government-sponsored lenders [[Fannie Mae]] and [[Freddie Mac]] to buy more home loans issued to poor homeowners, in an attempt to end discrimination against minorities.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/nyregion/24hud.html |title=As HUD Chief, Cuomo Earns a Mixed Score |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 23, 2010 |author1=David M. Halbfinger |author2=Michael Powell |accessdate=September 17, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127034455/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/nyregion/24hud.html |archivedate=January 27, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some believe that this helped lead to the 2007-2010 [[subprime mortgage crisis]].<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" /><ref name=\"Barrett\">{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-08-05/news/how-andrew-cuomo-gave-birth-to-the-crisis-at-fannie-mae-and-freddie-mac/ |title=Andrew Cuomo and Fannie and Freddie |work=[[The Village Voice]] |date=August 5, 2008 |accessdate=September 17, 2010 |first=Wayne |last=Barrett |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722145449/http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-08-05/news/how-andrew-cuomo-gave-birth-to-the-crisis-at-fannie-mae-and-freddie-mac/ |archivedate=July 22, 2010 }}</ref> Edward J. Pinto, former chief credit officer at Fannie Mae, said \"they should have known the risks were large. Cuomo was pushing mortgage bankers to make loans and basically saying you have to offer a loan to everybody.\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" /> But others disagree with the assessment that Cuomo caused the crisis. [[Dean Baker]], co-director of the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]], said Cuomo \"was a contributor in terms of him being a cheerleader, but I don't think we can pin too much blame on him.\"<ref name=\"Fairbanks\" />\n\nAccording to libertarian author and critic [[James Bovard]], Cuomo was obsessed with changing HUD's image, as Cuomo declared, \"The PR is the important thing I do ... Eighty percent of the battle is communications.\" He championed a new program called Community Builders, created without appropriation by Congress, for 800 new HUD employees with computers to be paid as much as $100,000. In a June 16, 1999, speech, Cuomo declared that one purpose of the program was to fight against HUD's abolition. In August 1999, Community Builders distributed a letter to community groups to fight against proposed tax cuts. One HUD official declared that Community Builders were seen as \"Democratic [[ward heeler]]s who act as a pipeline between Democratic city officials, party leaders, and the administration and the [[Democratic National Committee]].\"\n\nIn 1998, Clinton-appointed HUD inspector general Susan Gaffney testified to a Senate committee that she was the victim of \"'escalating' attacks on her office by Cuomo and 'his key aides,' including cooked-up charges of racism, insubordination, malfeasance, and general dirty-dealing.\" In 1999, Gaffney's office concluded that \"most (15 out of 19) Community Builders' goals were activities rather than actual accomplishments.\" and that Cuomo's initiatives \"had a crippling effect on many of HUD's ongoing operations.\"<ref>{{cite book | first=James | last=Bovard | authorlink=James Bovard | year= 2000 | title= Feeling Your Pain: The Explosion and Abuse Of Government Power in the Clinton-Gore Years | publisher= St. Martin's Press | location= New York | id=0-312-23082-6 | pages= 182\u2013184}}</ref>  Gaffney retired in May 2001, shortly after the department reached a $490,000 settlement with a black employee who had accused her of racial discrimination in passing him over for a promotion.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nakashima |first=Ellen |agency=''[[Washington Post]]'' |date=May 6, 2001 |title=HUD's Inspector General Retiring After Racial-Bias Suit Settlement |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/fl-xpm-2001-05-06-0105060155-story.html |work=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |location=Deerfield Beach, FL}}</ref>\n\nPrior to Cuomo's tenure, HUD was routinely included on the General Accounting Office's biannual watch list of government programs whose poor management made them prone to fraud.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite news |last=Mahler |first=Jonathan |date=August 11, 2010 |title=The Making of Andrew Cuomo |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/15/magazine/15Cuomo-t.html |work=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |location=New York, NY |url-access=subscription |page=30}}</ref> During his time in office, two of HUD's four main departments were removed from the GAO list.<ref name=\"Making\"/> In addition, the department cut 15 percent of its staff as part of a Cuomo initiative to streamline its operations.<ref name=\"Making\"/>\n\n== 2002 New York gubernatorial election ==\n{{see also|2002 New York gubernatorial election}}\nCuomo first ran for the Democratic nomination for Governor of New York in 2002. He was initially the favorite for nomination and led in fund-raising and polls, but his campaign took serious damage after a [[gaffe]] when Cuomo said (in reference to the aftermath of the [[September 11 attacks]]) \"[[George Pataki|Pataki]] stood behind the leader. He held the leader's coat. He was a great assistant to the leader. But he was not a leader. Cream rises to the top, and [[Rudy Giuliani]] rose to the top.\" His remarks were widely derided; even his father, former governor [[Mario Cuomo]], later admitted it was a blunder.<ref name=\"Dreher\">{{cite news|first=Rod|last=Dreher |url=http://www.nationalreview.com/dreher/dreher090402.asp|title=Where the Son Doesn't Follow|work=[[National Review]]|date=September 4, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020910104631/http://www.nationalreview.com/dreher/dreher090402.asp|archivedate=September 10, 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn the eve of the state convention, Cuomo withdrew from consideration after concluding that he had little chance of support as opposed to the favored party candidate, [[New York State Comptroller|State Comptroller]] [[Carl McCall]].<ref name=\"Schneider\">{{cite news| first=Bill| last=Schneider| url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/09/06/ip.pol.umbrella/index.html|title=Let a political connection be your umbrella?|work=Inside Politics|publisher=CNN|date=September 6, 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050319094326/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/09/06/ip.pol.umbrella/index.html|archivedate=March 19, 2005}}</ref> McCall went on to lose the general election to [[George Pataki]].\n\n== New York attorney general ==\n=== Election ===\n{{main|2006 New York Attorney General election}}\nCuomo declared his candidacy for the Democratic nomination for [[New York State Attorney General|New York State attorney general]] in 2006, and on May 30, 2006, captured the Democratic Party's endorsement, receiving 65% of the delegates. Though Cuomo won the endorsement, former [[New York City Public Advocate|New York City public advocate]] [[Mark J. Green]] and two-time candidate for [[Lieutenant Governor of New York|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Charlie King (politician)|Charlie King]], also earned places on the Democratic [[primary election|ballot]].<ref name=\"Hicks\">{{cite news|first=Jonathan P.|last=Hicks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/31/nyregion/31ag.html|title=Cuomo Wins Democrats' Backing in Primary Race for Attorney General|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 31, 2006|accessdate=July 23, 2007}}</ref> King dropped out of the race before the primary and endorsed Cuomo.<ref name=\"NYDailyNews022610\">{{cite news|first=Elizabeth|last=Benjamin|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/02/sharpton-praises-paterson-wont.html|title=Sharpton Praises Paterson, Won't Endorse Cuomo Today | location=New York |work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|date=February 26, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100303002407/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/02/sharpton-praises-paterson-wont.html|archivedate=March 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nCuomo won the primary with a majority of the vote, defeating his nearest opponent by over 20%. Clinching the Democratic party nomination was considered a significant rebound following his unsuccessful and unpopular 2002 gubernatorial campaign and at the nominating convention, June O'Neill, the Democratic chairwoman of [[St. Lawrence County]], called him \"New York's own Comeback Kid.\"<ref name=\"Hicks\" /> He won the [[general election]] against the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee, former [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]] [[District attorney]] [[Jeanine Pirro]] on November 7, 2006, winning 58% of the vote.\n\n=== Tenure ===\n==== Police surveillance, 2007 ====\n{{main|Eliot Spitzer political surveillance controversy}}\nOn July 23, 2007, Cuomo's office admonished the [[Eliot Spitzer|Spitzer administration]] for ordering the State Police to keep special records of then-Senate majority leader [[Joseph Bruno]]'s whereabouts when he traveled with police escorts in New York City.<ref name=\"nyt072307\">{{cite news|first=Danny|last=Hakim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/23/nyregion/23cnd-spitzer.html|title=Spitzer's Staff Misused Police, Report Finds|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 23, 2007|accessdate=July 24, 2007}}</ref> At the discretion of top officials of the Spitzer administration, the [[New York State Police]] created documents meant to cause political damage to Bruno.<ref name=\"ijour072307\">{{cite news|first=Cara |last=Matthews |url=http://www.theithacajournal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070723/NEWS01/70723006/1002 |title=Cuomo: Spitzer aides used state police to try to damage Bruno |work=[[The Ithaca Journal]] |date=July 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://m.lohud.com/detail.jsp?key=62289&full=1 |archivedate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref> Spitzer responded by accepting responsibility and issuing an apology to Bruno.<ref name=\"nyt072307\" /><ref name=\"siadv\">{{cite news |first=Sally |last=Goldenberg |url=http://blog.silive.com/advanceupdate/2007/07/report_governor_office_compil.html|title=Report: Governor's office compiled, leaked data on Bruno |work=[[Staten Island Advance]] |date=July 23, 2007 |accessdate=July 24, 2007}}{{dead link|date=February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Student loan inquiry, 2007 ====\nIn 2007, Cuomo was active in a high-profile investigation into lending practices and anti-competitive relationships between student lenders and universities. Specifically, many universities steered student borrowers to a \"preferred lender,\" which resulted in the borrowers' incurring higher interest rates. This led to changes in lending policy at many major American universities. Many universities also rebated millions of dollars in fees back to affected borrowers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/banking/2007-04-10-cuomo-student-loan-probe_N.htm |title=Cuomo: School loan corruption widespread|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=April 8, 2008| date=April 10, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Doug|last=Lederman|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2007/05/15/texas|title=The First Casualty|publisher=Inside Higher Education|date=May 15, 2007|accessdate=April 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:CuomoAckerman.jpg|thumb|240px|Cuomo with Representative [[Gary Ackerman]]]]\n\n==== Usenet, 2008 ====\nOn June 10, 2008, Cuomo announced that three major Internet service providers ([[Verizon Communications]], [[Time Warner Cable]], and [[Sprint Nextel|Sprint]]) would \"shut down major sources of online [[child pornography]]\" by no longer hosting many [[Usenet]] groups. Time Warner Cable ceased offering Usenet altogether, Sprint ended access to the 18,408 newsgroups in the [[alt.* hierarchy]], and Verizon limited its Usenet offerings to the approximately 3,000 [[Big 8 (Usenet)|Big 8]] newsgroups. The move came after Cuomo's office located 88 different newsgroups to which child pornography had been posted.<ref>Rosencrance, Lisa. \"[http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&articleId=9095778 3 top ISPs to block access to sources of child porn].\" ''[[Computer World]]''. June 8, 2008. Retrieved September 23, 2010.</ref><ref name=\"DeJeanNotDeadYet2\">DeJean, David. \"Usenet: Not Dead Yet.\" ''[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]''. Tuesday October 7, 2008. [https://www.pcworld.com/article/151989-2/usenet_not_dead_yet.html 2]. Retrieved September 23, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=McCullagh | first= Declan | title= N.Y. attorney general forces ISPs to curb Usenet access | url= http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-9964895-38.html | date= June 10, 2008 | publisher=CNET News | accessdate=April 28, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==== 2008 Obama remarks ====\nIn 2008, Cuomo said of the Democratic Party candidate [[Barack Obama]], who was running against [[Hillary Clinton]], the candidate Cuomo supported: \"You can't shuck and jive at a press conference.\" Cuomo received criticism from some for his use of the phrase. [[Roland S. Martin|Roland Martin]] of [[CNN]] said that \"'[[shuckin' and jivin']]' have long been words used as a negative assessment of African Americans, along the lines of a 'foot-shufflin' [[Negro]].'\"<ref>[http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2008/01/11/martin-shucking-and-jiving-and-the-campaign-trail/ \"Martin: 'Shucking and jiving' and the campaign trail\"], CNN Political Ticker \u2013 CNN.com Blogs, January 11, 2008.</ref>\n\n==== Corruption and fraud investigations, 2009 ====\nCuomo investigated a corruption scandal, \"fraudulent scheme to extract kickbacks\", which involved New York investigators, the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]], and [[state attorney general|attorneys general]] in dozens of states.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/15/business/15leuschen.html Go-Between Tied Funds to Carlyle]. New York Times, May 14, 2009</ref>\n\nAlso in 2009, Cuomo launched a suit against the [[United Homeless Organization]], a New York charity. He charged that the majority of the group's income was not used to provide services to the homeless, but was diverted to the founders for unrelated personal expenses.<ref name=\"nyp_20091123\">{{citation | title=Homeless beggar jars a sham: AG | publisher=[[New York Post]] | date=2009-11-24 | url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/suit_put_cork_in_it_jugheads_GvF3qaHCib8Xh5AY86i68O?offset=16#comments#ixzz0Xmpl4OA1 | accessdate=2009-11-24 | first1=Melissa | last1=Klein | first2=Kevin | last2=Fasick | first3=Chuck | last3=Bennett}}</ref> In 2010, Judge [[Barbara R. Kapnick]] granted the judgement and forced the group to disband.<ref name=\"UHO Shut Down\">{{cite news| url= http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/judge_rules_hucksters_permanently_ahPPxEVrVEHlimCcLjlQ4I| title=Judge rules to permanently shut down faux homeless charity, but hucksters still out in force|last=Bennett|first=Chuck|date=|work=New York Post|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Potential U.S. Senate appointment ==\n{{See also|United States Senate special election in New York, 2010#Potential candidates|l1=Possible appointment choices for the New York Senate seat}}\nAfter [[Hillary Clinton]] became President Obama's choice for [[U.S. Secretary of State|U.S. secretary of state]], then-New York governor [[David Paterson]] was charged with appointing a temporary replacement until a [[United States Senate special election in New York, 2010|special election]]. Cuomo was seen as a leading contender for this appointment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/22/us/politics/22hillary.html|title=If Clinton Should Win, Who Would Take Her Place?|accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=January 22, 2007|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Chan, Sewell |author2= Richard P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a}}</ref><ref name=WaHfCS /> [[Caroline Kennedy]] (also the first cousin of Cuomo's ex-wife) was another leading contender, but withdrew for personal reasons two days before Paterson was set to announce his choice, leaving Cuomo and U.S. representative [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] as the most likely appointees.<ref name=WaHfCS>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/04/us/politics/04senateseat.html|title=Wishing and Hoping for Clinton's Seat|accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=October 4, 2007|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hakim, Danny}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/22/nyregion/22york.html|title=New York Weighs Options to Fill the Seat of Senator Clinton |accessdate=November 23, 2008|date=November 21, 2008|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Hakim, Danny| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081210011131/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/22/nyregion/22york.html| archivedate= December 10, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> On January 23, Paterson announced he would appoint Gillibrand to the U.S. Senate.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/01/23/gillibrand.profile/index.html | title=N.Y. governor names Clinton successor | author=Silverleib, Alan |publisher=CNN | date=January 23, 2009 | accessdate=January 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Governor of New York ==\n=== Elections ===\n==== 2010 ====\n{{main|2010 New York gubernatorial election}}\nOn September 18, 2009, advisors to President Barack Obama informed Governor [[David Paterson]] that the president believed he should withdraw his 2010 gubernatorial candidacy, stepping aside for \"popular Attorney General Andrew Cuomo.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/news/region-state/obama-cordial-but-cool-to-gov-paterson-1.1465587 |title=Obama cordial but cool to Gov. David Paterson |work=Newsday |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2010}}</ref> On January 23, 2010, the New York ''Daily News'' reported that Cuomo would announce plans for a gubernatorial campaign at the end of March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2010/01/23/2010-01-23_source_says_andrew_cuomo_will_announce_plans_to_run_for_new_york_governor_in_mar.html| title=Source says Andrew Cuomo will announce plans to run for New York Governor in March|date=January 23, 2010|accessdate=January 24, 2010|author=Molloy, Joanna|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]| location=New York | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100127181447/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/2010/01/23/2010-01-23_source_says_andrew_cuomo_will_announce_plans_to_run_for_new_york_governor_in_mar.html| archivedate= January 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Later reports indicated Cuomo would announce his gubernatorial campaign coinciding with the state Democratic Convention in late May.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=ao6UppVoMprA |title=Cuomo Said to Wait for N.Y. Convention to Declare Governor Run |publisher=Bloomberg |date=May 30, 2005 |accessdate=May 16, 2010 |first=Henry |last=Goldman}}</ref> On May 22, 2010, Cuomo announced his run for governor in a video posted to his campaign website. Cuomo announced his choice for lieutenant governor on May 26, 2010: Mayor of [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]].<ref name=\"DuffySelection\">{{cite news|url=http://rochester.ynn.com/content/top_stories/505988/cuomo-names-mayor-duffy-as-running-mate/|title=Cuomo Names Mayor Duffy as Running Mate|work=Your News Now (YNN) Rochester|date=May 26, 2010|accessdate=February 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the November 2, 2010, general election, Cuomo faced Republican [[Carl Paladino]], a [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]]-based businessman who had been heavily supported by the [[Tea Party movement]]. Cuomo won the election for governor by a landslide, winning 62.6% of the vote. Paladino performed strongly in his native Buffalo area, while Cuomo performed well in the eastern part of the state as well as downstate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article187686.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208193115/http://www.buffalonews.com/city/article187686.ece|url-status=dead|title=\"Long Islanders put Paladino to test as their cup of tea,\" ''Buffalo News'', September 12, 2010.|archivedate=February 8, 2012}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n[[File:NYGov10County.png|thumb|Election results by county]]\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- style=\"background-color:#E9E9E9\"\n! colspan=\"7\" | New York gubernatorial general election results, 2010 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2010/general/2010GovernorRecertified09122012.pdf |title=NYS Board of Elections Governor/Lt. Governor Election Returns November 2, 2010 |accessdate=2013-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105210422/http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2010/general/2010GovernorRecertified09122012.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2013 }}</ref>\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#eeeeee\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 15em\" |Party\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Candidate\n! style=\"width: 10em\" |Running mate\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Votes\n! style=\"width: 7em\" |Percentage\n! style=\"width: 5em\" |Swing\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#3333FF; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 2,609,465\n| align=\"right\" | 56.52%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 1.82%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#CC6699; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Working Families Party|Working Families]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 154,835\n| align=\"right\" | 3.35%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 0.05%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#800080; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Independence Party of New York|Independence]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Andrew Cuomo''\n| align=\"right\" | 146,576\n| align=\"right\" | 3.17%\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 0.89%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#B2BEB5; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | Total\n| '''Andrew Cuomo'''\n| '''[[Robert Duffy (politician)|Robert Duffy]]'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''2,910,876'''\n| align=\"right\" | '''63.05%'''\n| align=\"right\" | {{decrease}} 2.65%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF3333; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''Carl Paladino''\n| align=\"right\" | 1,289,817\n| align=\"right\" | 27.94%\n| align=\"right\" | {{increase}} 4.40%\n|-\n! style=\"background-color:#FF8C00; width: 3px\" |\n| style=\"width: 130px\" | [[Conservative Party of 