{"title_page": "Grays railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Grays\n| symbol        = rail\n| alt_name      =\n| manager       = [[c2c]]\n| manager1      =\n| owner         = [[Network Rail]]\n| owner1        =\n| locale        = [[Grays, Essex|Grays]]\n| borough       = [[Thurrock]]\n| platforms     = 3\n| fare_zone     = A\n| railcode      = GRY\n| dft_category  = C2\n| image_name    = Grays railway station, Essex (geograph 3760214).jpg\n| image_alt     =\n| caption       = Main building, London-bound side\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.476|0.322|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type      = Essex\n| access        = yes\n| access_note   = <ref>{{citation step free south east rail}}</ref>\n| years1        = {{start date|1854}}\n| events1       = Opened\n<!--\n| railexits0405 = {{pad}}2.374\n| railexits0506 = {{increase}} 2.381\n| railexits0607 = {{increase}} 2.600\n| railexits0708 = {{decrease}} 2.884\n| railexits0809 = {{decrease}} 2.862\n| railexits0910 = {{decrease}} 2.788\n| railexits1011 = {{increase}} 2.835\n| railexits1112 = {{increase}} 2.972\n| railexits1213 = {{increase}} 3.091\n| railexits1314 = {{increase}} 3.224-->\n| railexits1415 = {{increase}} 3.471\n| railexits1516 = {{increase}} 3.819\n| railexits1617 = {{increase}} 3.985\n| railexits1718 = {{increase}} 4.053\n| railexits1819 = {{increase}} 4.165\n}}\n'''Grays railway station''' is on the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]] line serving the town of [[Grays, Essex|Grays]], Essex. It is {{convert|19|mi|70|chain|km}} down the line from [[Fenchurch Street railway station|London Fenchurch Street]] via {{rws|Rainham|Essex}} and is located at the junction where a branch line from {{stn|Upminster}} via {{rws|Ockendon}} re-joins the route from Rainham. Its three-letter station code is GRY.\n\nIt was opened in 1854. The station and all trains serving it are currently operated by [[c2c]]. Although outside the London fare zones, the station became part of the [[Oyster card]] pay-as-you-go network in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/mayor-decisions/docs/20091015-md457-fares-2010.pdf|publisher=Greater London Authority|title=Request for Mayoral Decision \u2013 MD457. Title:  January 2010 Fare Changes|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mReAWXEY?url=http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/mayor-decisions/docs/20091015-md457-fares-2010.pdf|archivedate=1 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIt was opened in 1854 on the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]]. Until the early 1900s the station was known as '''Grays Thurrock'''. \n\nIn 2005 the station environment was refurbished, in particular the subway linking the platforms, and the surrounding highway infrastructure. In January 2006 the footbridge linking Grays High Street at either side of the railway was declared unsafe and closed due to structural problems with the supports and bracing, which had to be temporarily supported with scaffolding underneath the stair flights. A hoarding was subsequently erected on this scaffolding.  The footbridge reopened in May 2006.  Works to replace the stair flights have been completed. Although located at the end of the platforms, there is no station access at this point.\n\nDuring 2008 and 2009 the four-carriage bay platform was extended to hold eight-coach trains. From 2011 to 2012 the through platforms were extended to receive 12-coach trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c2c-online.co.uk/latest_updates/news/new_timetable_changes_postponement |title=New Timetable Changes Postponement |accessdate=2008-10-26 |publisher=c2c |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316003828/http://www.c2c-online.co.uk/latest_updates/news/new_timetable_changes_postponement |archivedate=16 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe typical off-peak service frequency is:\n\n* 4 trains per hour (tph) westbound to [[Fenchurch Street railway station|London Fenchurch Street]], of which:\n** 2 via {{rws|Rainham|Essex}};\n** 2 via {{rws|Ockendon}}.\n* 2 tph eastbound to {{rws|Southend Central}}.\n\n==Connections==\n\nLocal bus routes Z1, 22, 22A, 25, 33, 44, 66, 73, 73A, 83, 88, 100, 100X, 200, 200X, 201, 265, 268, 269, and 374 all serve the station.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{stn art lnk|GRY|RM176NQ}}\n{{commons category|Grays railway station}}\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line two to one|previous1=[[Chafford Hundred Lakeside railway station|Chafford Hundred Lakeside]]|previous2=[[Purfleet railway station|Purfleet]]|next=[[Tilbury Town railway station|Tilbury Town]]|route1=[[c2c]]<br><small>[[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway|London, Tilbury and Southend Line]]<br>via Ockendon|route2=[[c2c]]<br><small>[[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway|London, Tilbury and Southend Line]]<br>via Rainham</small>|\n</small>|col={{C2C colour}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Transport in Thurrock]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Essex]]\n[[Category:Former London, Tilbury and Southend Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1854]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by c2c]]\n[[Category:Grays]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox London station\n| name          = Grays\n| symbol        = rail\n| alt_name      =\n| manager       = [[c2c]]\n| manager1      =\n| owner         = [[Network Rail]]\n| owner1        =\n| locale        = [[Grays]]\n| borough       = [[Thurrock]]\n| platforms     = 3\n| fare_zone     = A\n| railcode      = GRY\n| dft_category  = C2\n| image_name    = Grays railway station, Essex (geograph 3760214).jpg\n| image_alt     =\n| caption       = Main building, London-bound side\n| coordinates   = {{coord|51.476|0.322|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type      = Essex\n| access        = yes\n| access_note   = <ref>{{citation step free south east rail}}</ref>\n| years1        = {{start date|1854}}\n| events1       = Opened\n<!--\n| railexits0405 = {{pad}}2.374\n| railexits0506 = {{increase}} 2.381\n| railexits0607 = {{increase}} 2.600\n| railexits0708 = {{decrease}} 2.884\n| railexits0809 = {{decrease}} 2.862\n| railexits0910 = {{decrease}} 2.788\n| railexits1011 = {{increase}} 2.835\n| railexits1112 = {{increase}} 2.972\n| railexits1213 = {{increase}} 3.091\n| railexits1314 = {{increase}} 3.224-->\n| railexits1415 = {{increase}} 3.471\n| railexits1516 = {{increase}} 3.819\n| railexits1617 = {{increase}} 3.985\n| railexits1718 = {{increase}} 4.053\n| railexits1819 = {{increase}} 4.165\n}}\n'''Grays railway station''' is on the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]] line serving the town of [[Grays]], Essex. It is {{convert|19|mi|70|chain|km}} down the line from [[Fenchurch Street railway station|London Fenchurch Street]] via {{rws|Rainham|Essex}} and is located at the junction where a branch line from {{stn|Upminster}} via {{rws|Ockendon}} re-joins the route from Rainham. Its three-letter station code is GRY.\n\nIt was opened in 1854. The station and all trains serving it are currently operated by [[c2c]]. Although outside the London fare zones, the station became part of the [[Oyster card]] pay-as-you-go network in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/mayor-decisions/docs/20091015-md457-fares-2010.pdf|publisher=Greater London Authority|title=Request for Mayoral Decision \u2013 MD457. Title:  January 2010 Fare Changes|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mReAWXEY?url=http://www.london.gov.uk/mayor/mayor-decisions/docs/20091015-md457-fares-2010.pdf|archivedate=1 January 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIt was opened in 1854 on the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]]. Until the early 1900s the station was known as '''Grays Thurrock'''. \n\nIn 2005 the station environment was refurbished, in particular the subway linking the platforms, and the surrounding highway infrastructure. In January 2006 the footbridge linking Grays High Street at either side of the railway was declared unsafe and closed due to structural problems with the supports and bracing, which had to be temporarily supported with scaffolding underneath the stair flights. A hoarding was subsequently erected on this scaffolding.  The footbridge reopened in May 2006.  Works to replace the stair flights have been completed. Although located at the end of the platforms, there is no station access at this point.\n\nDuring 2008 and 2009 the four-carriage bay platform was extended to hold eight-coach trains. From 2011 to 2012 the through platforms were extended to receive 12-coach trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c2c-online.co.uk/latest_updates/news/new_timetable_changes_postponement |title=New Timetable Changes Postponement |accessdate=2008-10-26 |publisher=c2c |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316003828/http://www.c2c-online.co.uk/latest_updates/news/new_timetable_changes_postponement |archivedate=16 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe typical off-peak service frequency is:\n\n* 4 trains per hour (tph) westbound to [[Fenchurch Street railway station|London Fenchurch Street]], of which:\n** 2 via {{rws|Rainham|Essex}};\n** 2 via {{rws|Ockendon}}.\n* 2 tph eastbound to {{rws|Southend Central}}.\n\n==Connections==\n\nLocal bus routes Z1, 22, 22A, 25, 33, 44, 66, 73, 73A, 83, 88, 100, 100X, 200, 200X, 201, 265, 268, 269, and 374 all serve the station.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{stn art lnk|GRY|RM176NQ}}\n{{commons category|Grays railway station}}\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line two to one|previous1=[[Chafford Hundred Lakeside railway station|Chafford Hundred Lakeside]]|previous2=[[Purfleet railway station|Purfleet]]|next=[[Tilbury Town railway station|Tilbury Town]]|route1=[[c2c]]<br><small>[[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway|London, Tilbury and Southend Line]]<br>via Ockendon|route2=[[c2c]]<br><small>[[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway|London, Tilbury and Southend Line]]<br>via Rainham</small>|\n</small>|col={{C2C colour}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n[[Category:Transport in Thurrock]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Essex]]\n[[Category:Former London, Tilbury and Southend Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1854]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by c2c]]\n[[Category:Grays]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGrays(link changed toGrays, Essex; link changed toGrays, Essex) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grays_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "Hunter Biden", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Son of former Vice President of the United States Joe Biden}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Hunter Biden\n|image        = R. Hunter Biden at Center for Strategic & International Studies.jpg\n|caption      = Biden at the [[Center for Strategic & International Studies]] in 2013\n|office       = Vice Chairman of the [[Amtrak|National Railroad Passenger Corporation]]\n|president    = George W. Bush<br>[[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start   = July 26, 2006\n|term_end     = January 29, 2009\n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = Donna McLean\n|birth_name   = Robert Hunter Biden\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|2|4}}\n|birth_place  = [[Wilmington, Delaware]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Kathleen Buhle|1993|2017|end=div}}<br>{{marriage|Melissa Cohen|2019}}\n|partner      = Hallie Olivere (2016\u20132018)\n|children     = 4\n|relatives    = [[Joe Biden]] (father)<br>''See [[Biden family]]''\n|education    = [[Georgetown University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|allegiance   = {{flagu|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears = 2013\u20132014\n|rank         = [[File:US Navy O1 infobox.svg|25px]] [[Ensign (United States)|Ensign]]\n|unit         = [[United States Navy Reserve]]\n}}\n'''Robert Hunter Biden''' (born February 4, 1970) is an American lawyer and lobbyist who is the second son of former [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]]. He co-founded Rosemont Seneca Partners, an international consulting firm, in 2009.\n\nBiden served on the board of [[Burisma Holdings]], a major [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] [[natural gas]] producer, from 2014 to 2019. He has been the subject of debunked right-wing [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] concerning his business dealings in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/world/2019/10/10/trumps-biden-ukraine-natural-gas-conspiracy-theory-false-but-alive/3851728002/|title=Trump's Biden-Ukraine natural gas conspiracy theory: False, but alive|website=USA Today |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/sep/30/trump-impeachment-five-conspiracy-theories-ukraine-dilemma|title=Five fantasies Trump is pushing about the Ukraine scandal \u2013 and the truth |website=The Guardian |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry/trump-pushing-baseless-conspiracy-about-bidens-china-here-s-what-n1062551|title=Trump is pushing a baseless conspiracy about the Bidens and China. Here's what we know. |publisher=NBC News |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/there-s-no-evidence-trump-s-biden-ukraine-accusations-what-n1057851|title=There's no evidence for Trump's Biden-Ukraine accusations. What really happened?|publisher=NBC News |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/9/23/20879611/joe-biden-hunter-biden-ukraine-corruption-prosecutor-burisma-donald-trump-whistleblower-complaint|title=The facts behind Trump's bogus accusations about Biden and Ukraine|website=Vox |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-invention-of-the-conspiracy-theory-on-biden-and-ukraine|title=The Invention of the Conspiracy Theory on Biden and Ukraine|website=The New Yorker |access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/internet/sondland-testified-misleading-ukraine-story-spread-among-conservatives-social-media-n1087511|title=As Sondland testified, a misleading Ukraine story spread among conservatives on social media|publisher=NBC News |access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal|President Donald Trump's alleged attempt to pressure the Ukrainian government]] to investigate Joe Biden and Hunter Biden by withholding foreign aid<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/24/donald-trump-ukraine-military-aid-1509070|title=Trump changes story on withholding Ukraine aid|last=Forgey|first=Quint|website=[[Politico]]|date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/giuliani-says-he-can-t-be-100-percent-sure-trump-n1057561|title=Trump suggests he tied Ukraine funding to corruption, cites Biden allegations|last1=Pettypiece|first1=Shannon|last2=Smith|first2=Allan|date=September 23, 2019|publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/9/20/20875471/rudy-giuliani-chris-cuomo-cnn-meltdown-trump-ukraine-cnn |title=Rudy Giuliani's viral CNN meltdown over Trump and Ukraine, briefly explained |last=Rupar |first=Aaron |date=September 20, 2019 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> triggered an [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|impeachment inquiry]] in September 2019.\n\nIn October 2019, Biden resigned from the Board of Directors of a Chinese private investment fund he co-founded, [[BHR Partners]], saying he wanted to avoid even the appearance of a conflict of interest while his father was running for president.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/10/13/20912336/hunter-biden-resigns-chinese-firm-impeachment-inquiry-joe-trump|title=Hunter Biden resigns from a Chinese firm amid controversy over his business dealings|website=Vox|last=van Wagtendonk|first=Anya|date=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=CNBC191013/>\n\n==Early life==\n{{Further|Biden family}}\nBiden was born on February 4, 1970,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hunter-biden-denies-ashley-madison-account-belongs/story?id=33301506|title=Hunter Biden Denies Ashley Madison Account Is His |first1=Jordyn |last1=Phelps |first2=Arlette |last2=Saenz |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=August 25, 2015 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> in [[Wilmington, Delaware]]. He is the second son of Neilia Biden (n\u00e9e Hunter) and [[Joe Biden]], who served in the [[United States Senate]] from 1973 to 2009 and as [[Vice President of the United States]] from 2009 to 2017.<ref name=\"entous1\">{{cite news |last1=Entous |first1=Adam |title=Will Hunter Biden Jeopardize His Father's Campaign? |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/07/08/will-hunter-biden-jeopardize-his-fathers-campaign |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=July 1, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Hunter Biden's mother and younger sister, Naomi, were killed in an automobile crash on December 18, 1972.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Connelly |title=Biden shows more bark than bite |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7585384.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |location=London, England |date= August 28, 2008 |accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=John M.|last=Broder|title=Biden Opens New Phase With Attack on McCain |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/28/us/politics/28biden.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date= August 28, 2008|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Biden and his older brother [[Beau Biden|Beau]] were also seriously injured.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> Hunter and Beau Biden later encouraged their father to marry again,<ref>{{cite news |first=Katharine Q.|last=Seelye|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/25/us/politics/25wife.html |title=Jill Biden Heads Toward Life in the Spotlight |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210193454/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/25/us/politics/25wife.html |archivedate=December 10, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jill Biden|Jill Jacobs]] became Hunter and Beau's stepmother in 1977.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> Biden's half-sister, Ashley, was born in 1981.<ref name=\"newman1\">{{cite news |last1=Newman |first1=Meredith |last2=Jagtiani |first2=Sarika |last3=Sharp |first3=Andrew |title=Hunter Biden: Who is former Vice President Joe Biden's son mentioned in Ukraine-Trump call? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/09/26/who-hunter-biden-joe-biden-son-ukraine-call/3773527002/ |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLike his father and brother, Biden attended [[Archmere Academy]], a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] high school in [[Claymont, Delaware]].<ref name=\"entous1\" /> In 1992, he graduated from [[Georgetown University]] with a bachelor's degree in history.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> During the year after he graduated from college, he served as a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] volunteer at a church in [[Portland, Oregon]], where he met Kathleen Buhle, whom he married in 1993.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> After attending [[Georgetown University Law Center]] for one year, he transferred to [[Yale Law School]], graduating in 1996.<ref name=\"entous1\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Early positions, 1996\u20132009===\n\nAfter graduating from law school, Biden took a position at [[MBNA]] America, a major [[bank holding]] company which was also a major contributor to his father's political campaigns.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> By 1998, he had risen to the rank of executive vice president.<ref name=\"entous1\" /><ref>{{cite news |first1=Matthew |last1=Yglesias |authorlink1=Matthew Yglesias |title=Hunter Biden, the black sheep who might accidentally bring down Trump, explained |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/10/1/20891510/hunter-biden-burisma-ukraine-shokin |work=Vox |date=October 1, 2019 |accessdate=October 24, 2019 |quote=There's no reason to think that Biden backed MBNA's position because his son worked there \u2014 senators normally line up with their home state's major employers' policy priorities \u2014 it's more like Hunter got the job due to his dad's overall cozy relationship with the company.}}</ref> From 1998 to 2001, he served in the [[United States Department of Commerce]], focusing on [[ecommerce]] policy.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peligri |first1=Justin |title=Who is Hunter Biden? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2014/10/17/politics/who-is-hunter-biden/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=October 18, 2014 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Biden became a lobbyist in 2001, co-founding the firm of Oldaker, Biden & Belair.<ref name=\"bschrekinger1\" /> According to Adam Entous of ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Biden and his father established a relationship in which \"Biden wouldn't ask Hunter about his lobbying clients, and Hunter wouldn't tell his father about them.\"<ref name=\"entous1\" /> In 2006, Biden and his uncle, James Biden, attempted to buy Paradigm, a hedge-fund group, but the deal fell apart before completion.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> That same year he was appointed by President [[George W. Bush]] to a five-year term on the board of directors of [[Amtrak]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Glass |first=Andrew |date=February 7, 2007 |title=A Younger Biden Goes the Extra Miles for Amtrak |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2007/02/a-younger-biden-goes-the-extra-miles-for-amtrak-002672 |work=Politico |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> He was a board member from July 2006 until he resigned in February 2009,<ref>{{cite news |last=Seitz |first=Amanda |date=October 21, 2019 |title=Hunter Biden didn't make millions off Amtrak |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8002831726 |publisher=Associated Press}}</ref> and the board's vice chairman from July 2006 to January 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pennfedbmwe.org/Docs/amtrak/Amtrak_Board/McLean/20090130_Amtrak_Advisory_McLean.pdf |title=Amtrak Board Names Thomas Carper of Illinois as Chairman: Former Chairman Donna McLean Becomes Vice Chairman |date=January 30, 2009 |website=pennfedbmwe.org |publisher=National Railroad Passenger Corporation |location=Washington, D.C. |page=1}}</ref> leaving both roles shortly after his father became vice president. He had realized during his father's vice presidential campaign that it was time for his lobbying activities to end.<ref name=\"entous1\" />\n\n===Later career, 2009\u2013present===\nIn 2009, Biden, along with Devon Archer and [[John Kerry]]'s stepson [[Christopher Heinz]], founded the investment firm Rosemont Seneca.<ref name=\"bschrekinger1\">{{cite news |last1=Schrekinger |first1=Ben |title=Biden Inc. |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/08/02/joe-biden-investigation-hunter-brother-hedge-fund-money-2020-campaign-227407 |work=Politico Magazine |date=August 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also joined the law firm [[Boies Schiller Flexner LLP]],<ref name=\"entous1\" /> and founded Eudora Global, a venture capital firm.<ref name=\"newman1\" />\n\n====U.S. Navy Reserve====\nIn May 2013, Biden's application for a position in the [[U.S. Navy Reserve]] was approved.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-son-hunter-discharged-from-navy-reserve-after-failing-cocaine-test-1413499657|title=Biden's Son Hunter Discharged From Navy Reserve After Failing Cocaine Test|last=Nelson|first=Colleen McCain|date=October 16, 2014|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |last2=Barnes |first2=Julian E. |issn=0099-9660 |access-date=May 3, 2019}}</ref> At age 43, Biden was accepted as part of a program that allows a limited number of applicants with desirable skills to receive commissions and serve in staff positions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ziezulewicz |first=Geoff |date=October 25, 2019 |title=The people Priebus beat out to become an ensign |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-navy/2019/10/25/the-people-priebus-beat-out-to-become-an-ensign/ |work=Military Times |location=Springfield, VA}}</ref> He received an age-related waiver and a waiver due to a past drug-related incident, and was sworn in as a [[direct commission officer]].<ref name=\"wsj\" /> Joe Biden administered his commissioning oath in a [[White House]] ceremony.<ref name=\"entous1\" />\n\nThe following month, Biden tested positive for [[cocaine]] during a urinalysis test and was subsequently discharged.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/article/1618324/us-navy-expelled-vice-president-bidens-son-after-positive-cocaine-test |agency=Agence France-Presse |title=US Navy expelled Vice-President Biden's son after positive cocaine test|date=October 17, 2014|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=October 17, 2014}}</ref> Biden attributed the result to smoking cigarettes he had accepted from other smokers, only later suspecting they had been laced with the drug.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> He chose not to appeal the matter as it was unlikely that the panel would believe his explanation given his history with drugs, and also due to the likelihood of news leaking to the press, though it was ultimately revealed to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' by a Navy official who provided information to the newspaper on condition of anonymity.<ref name=\"entous1\" /><ref name=\"wsj\" />\n\n====BHR Partners====\nIn 2013, Biden, Devon Archer, and Chinese businessman Jonathan Li founded [[BHR Partners]], a business focused on investing Chinese capital in companies based outside of [[China]].<ref name=\"entous1\" /> In September 2019, President Trump falsely claimed that Biden \"walk[ed] out of China with $1.5 billion in a fund\" and earned \"millions\" of dollars from the BHR deal, while Trump was also accusing Biden of malfeasance in Ukraine.<ref name=\"kessler-china\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/09/26/trumps-false-claims-about-hunter-bidens-china-dealings/|title=Trump's false claims about Hunter Biden's China dealings |first=Glenn |last=Kessler |authorlink=Glenn Kessler (journalist) |date=September 26, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/politics/fact-check-trump-bidens-china/index.html |date=October 4, 2019 |title=Fact-checking Trump's claims about the Bidens in China |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam |publisher=CNN |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Trump publicly called on China to investigate Hunter Biden's business activities there while his father was vice president.<ref>{{cite news |title=Explainer: Trump's claims and Hunter Biden's dealings in China |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-whistleblower-hunterbiden-c/explainer-trumps-claims-and-hunter-bidens-dealings-in-china-idUSKBN1WI2HK |agency=Reuters |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=What We Know About Hunter Biden's Business in China |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/hunter-biden-china.html |first=Sharon |last=LaFraniere |authorlink=Sharon LaFraniere |first2=Michael |last2=Forsythe |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 3, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> On October 13, 2019, citing \"the barrage of false charges\" by the President, Hunter Biden announced his resignation from the Board of Directors for BHR Partners effective at the end of the month.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=David |title=Hunter Biden to step down from board of Chinese company |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/13/hunter-biden-resign-china-company-045761 |work=Politico |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=CNBC191013>{{cite news |last1=Newburger |first1=Emma |title=Hunter Biden resigns from Chinese firm following Trump attacks |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/13/hunter-biden-resigns-from-chinese-firm-following-trump-attacks.html |publisher=CNBC |date=October 13, 2019 |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref> According to his lawyer, Biden had \"not received any compensation for being on BHR's board of directors,\" nor had he received any return on his equity share in BHR.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://medium.com/@george.mesires/a-statement-on-behalf-of-hunter-biden-dated-october-13-2019-d80bc11087ab |title=A Statement on behalf of Hunter Biden, dated October 13, 2019 |last=Mesires |first=George |website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |date=October 13, 2019 |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref> Biden's lawyer, George Mesires, told ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that BHR Partners had been \"capitalized from various sources with a total of 30 million RMB [Chinese [[Renminbi]]], or about $4.2 million, not $1.5 billion.\"<ref name=\"kessler-china\" />\n\n====Burisma Holdings====\nIn April 2014 after the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution|Ukrainian revolution]], Biden joined the board of [[Burisma Holdings]], one of the largest independent natural gas producers in [[Ukraine]]<ref name=\"entous1\" /> owned by an [[Ukrainian oligarch]] and former politician [[Mykola Zlochevsky]] who faced a money laundering investigation that time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/12/the-money-machine-how-a-high-profile-corruption-investigation-fell-apart |title=The money machine: how a high-profile corruption investigation fell apart |last=Bullough |first=Oliver |date=April 12, 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sonne1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Risen |first=James |authorlink=James Risen |date=December 8, 2015 |title=Joe Biden, His Son and the Case Against a Ukrainian Oligarch |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/09/world/europe/corruption-ukraine-joe-biden-son-hunter-biden-ties.html | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref> Biden, then an attorney with [[Boies Schiller Flexner LLP|Boies Schiller Flexner]], was hired to help Burisma with [[corporate governance]] [[best practice]]s, and a consulting firm in which Biden is a partner was also retained by Burisma.<ref name=nyt220919>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/22/us/politics/biden-ukraine-trump.html|title=Trump, Biden and Ukraine: Sorting Out the Accusations|first=Kenneth P.|last=Vogel|date=September 22, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"vogel-nyt\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/us/politics/biden-son-ukraine.html|title=Biden Faces Conflict of Interest Questions That Are Being Promoted by Trump and Allies|last=Vogel|first=Kenneth P.|date=May 1, 2019| newspaper =[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 29, 2019 | url-access = subscription |url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/b3Kow|archive-date=May 4, 2019|last2=Mendel|first2=Iuliia |issn=0362-4331|authorlink=Kenneth P. Vogel|author-link2=Iuliia Mendel}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2019/sep/23/president-donald-trump-ukraine-biden-whistleblower/|title=Trump's Ukraine call, a whistleblower and the Bidens: What we know, what we don't|last=Jacobson|first=Louis|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=September 24, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924204438/https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2019/sep/23/president-donald-trump-ukraine-biden-whistleblower/|archive-date=September 24, 2019|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|last2=Kruzel|first2=John}}</ref> Chris Heinz, [[John Kerry]]'s stepson, opposed his partners Devon Archer and Hunter Biden joining the board in 2014 due to the [[reputational risk]].<ref name=\"sonne1\" /> Biden served on the board of Burisma until his term expired in April 2019,<ref name=\"vogel-nyt\"/> receiving compensation of up to $50,000 per month in some months.<ref name=\"vogel-nyt\" /><ref name=nyt220919/> Because Vice President Biden played a major role in U.S. policy towards Ukraine, some Ukrainian anti-corruption advocates<ref name=\"braun1\" /><ref name=\"overlapped\" /> and [[presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] officials expressed concern that Hunter Biden's having joined the board could create the appearance of a [[conflict of interest]] and undermine Vice President Biden's anti-corruption work in Ukraine.<ref name=\"entous1\" /><ref name=\"sonne1\">{{cite news |last1=Sonne |first1=Paul |last2=Kranish |first2=Michael |last3=Viser |first3=Matt |title=The gas tycoon and the vice president's son: The story of Hunter Biden's foray into Ukraine |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/the-gas-tycoon-and-the-vice-presidents-son-the-story-of-hunter-bidens-foray-in-ukraine/2019/09/28/1aadff70-dfd9-11e9-8fd3-d943b4ed57e0_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> While serving as vice president, Joe Biden joined other Western leaders in encouraging the government of Ukraine to fire the country's top prosecutor, [[Viktor Shokin]],<ref name=\"kiely\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bump |first1=Philip |last2=Blake |first2=Aaron |title=The full Trump-Ukraine timeline \u2014 as of now |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/09/24/full-trump-ukraine-timeline-now/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> who was widely criticized for blocking corruption investigations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Daniel |title=EU hails sacking of Ukraine's prosecutor Viktor Shokin |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/eu-hails-sacking-of-ukraine-s-prosecutor-viktor-shokin-1.2591190 |work=The Irish Times |date=March 29, 2016 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/23/us/politics/trump-ukraine-collusion.html|title=Instead of 'No Collusion!' Trump Now Seems to Be Saying, So What if I Did?|first=Peter|last=Baker|authorlink=Peter Baker (journalist) |date=September 23, 2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019 | url-access = subscription}}</ref> The [[Verkhovna Rada|Ukrainian parliament]] voted to remove Shokin in March 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://iportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/page/en/news/News/127271.html |date=March 29, 2016 |title=News - Verkhovna Rada Chairperson Volodymyr Groysman calls on all people's deputies to take part in voting for dismissal of prosecutor general Shokin - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine |website=iportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=September 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/10/02/correcting-media-error-bidens-ukraine-showdown-was-december/ |title=Correcting a media error: Biden's Ukraine showdown was in December 2015 |last=Kessler |first=Glenn |authorlink=Glenn Kessler (journalist) |website=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 2, 2019 |accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, President Donald Trump and his personal lawyer, [[Rudy Giuliani]], claimed that Vice President Biden had actually sought the dismissal of Shokin in order to protect his son and Burisma Holdings,<ref name=\"raymond1\">{{cite news |last1=Raymond |first1=Adam K. |title=Everything We Know About the Joe Biden\u2013Ukraine Controversy |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/05/joe-biden-ukraine-controversy.html |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=May 7, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"braun1\">{{cite news |last1=Braun |first1=Stephen |last2=Berry |first2=Lynn |title=The story behind Biden's son, Ukraine and Trump's claims |url=https://www.apnews.com/9d4595ba4f3140c6bb6a3473a91f4a4c |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 23, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> however, there is no evidence that this was what happened and it was the official policy of the United States and the European Union to seek Shokin's removal.<ref name=\"kiely\">{{cite news |last1=Kiely |first1=Eugene |title=Trump Twists Facts on Biden and Ukraine |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2019/09/trump-twists-facts-on-biden-and-ukraine/ |work=[[FactCheck.org]] |publisher=Annenberg Public Policy Center |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt 2019-11-10\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/us/politics/joe-biden-ukraine.html|title=What Joe Biden Actually Did in Ukraine|first1=Glenn|last1=Thrush|first2=Kenneth P.|last2=Vogel|date=November 10, 2019 |newspaper=The New York Times | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref>In March 2016 testimony to the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], former ambassador to Ukraine [[John E. Herbst]] stated, \"By late fall of 2015, the EU and the United States joined the chorus of those seeking Mr. Shokin\u2019s removal\" and that Joe Biden \"spoke publicly about this before and during his December visit to Kyiv.\" During the same hearing, assistant secretary of state [[Victoria Nuland]] stated, \"we have pegged our next $1 billion loan guarantee, first and foremost, to having a rebooting of the reform coalition so that we know who we are working with, but secondarily, to ensuring that the prosecutor general\u2019s office gets cleaned up.\" https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/03%2015%2016%20Ukrainian%20Reforms%20Two%20Years%20After%20the%20Maidan%20Revolution%20and%20the%20Russian%20Invasion.pdf</ref> There has also been no evidence produced of wrongdoing done by Hunter Biden in Ukraine.<ref>Multiple sources:\n*{{cite news |title=Trump: I want to meet my accuser |url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/3954/trump-i-want-meet-my-accuser-doc-1kt4vy4 |date=September 30, 2019 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=US President Donald Trump said on Sunday he wants and deserves to meet the anonymous whistleblower at the center of the fast-moving scandal that has triggered an impeachment probe against him ... Brandishing what he said were affidavits incriminating Biden's son Hunter over his work at a Ukrainian company, Giuliani said Trump was duty bound to raise the issue with Kiev. Trump and his allies claim Biden, as Barack Obama's vice president, pressured Kiev to fire the country's top prosecutor to protect his son Hunter, who sat on the board of a gas company, Burisma Holdings, accused of corrupt practices. Those allegations have largely been debunked and there has been no evidence of illegal conduct or wrongdoing in Ukraine by the Bidens.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Matthias |first1=Williams |last2=Polityuk |first2=Pavel |title=Zelenskiy opponents say comments about Europeans to Trump could hurt Ukraine |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-trump-whistleblower-lawmaker-idAFL5N26H3HV |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=Trump pressed Zelenskiy to investigate the business dealings of the son of his political rival, former Vice President Joe Biden, the Democratic front-runner to challenge Trump in an election next year. Zelenskiy agreed. Biden's son Hunter worked for a company drilling for gas in Ukraine. There has been no evidence of wrongdoing by either Biden.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Isachenkov |first1=Vladimir |title=Ukraine's prosecutor says there is no probe into Biden |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/ukraines-prosecutor-says-there-is-no-probe-into-biden |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 27, 2019 |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=Though the timing raised concerns among anti-corruption advocates, there has been no evidence of wrongdoing by either the former vice president or his son.}}\n*{{cite news |title=White House 'tried to cover up details of Trump-Ukraine call' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49842895 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=There is no evidence of any wrongdoing by the Bidens.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Timm |first1=Jane |title=There's no evidence for Trump's Biden-Ukraine accusations. What really happened? |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/there-s-no-evidence-trump-s-biden-ukraine-accusations-what-n1057851 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 1, 2019 |quote=But despite Trump's continued claims, there's no evidence of wrongdoing on the part of either Biden.}}</ref> The Ukrainian anti-corruption investigation agency stated in September 2019 that the ''current'' investigation of Burisma was restricted solely to investigating the period of 2010 to 2012, before Hunter Biden joined Burisma in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ivanova |first1=Polina |last2=Polityuk |first2=Pavel |title=Ukraine agency says allegations against Burisma cover period before Biden joined |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-whistleblower-ukraine-buris/ukraine-agency-says-allegations-against-burisma-cover-period-before-biden-joined-idUSKBN1WC1LV |date=September 27, 2019 |agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Shokin in May 2019 claimed that he was fired because he had been actively investigating Burisma,<ref name=\"baker1\" /> but U.S. and Ukrainian officials have stated that the investigation into Burisma was dormant at the time of Shokin's dismissal.<ref name=\"sonne1\" /><ref name=\"baker1\">{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Stephanie |last2=Krasnolutska |first2=Daryna |title=Timeline in Ukraine Probe Casts Doubt on Giuliani's Biden Claim |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-07/timeline-in-ukraine-probe-casts-doubt-on-giuliani-s-biden-claim |work=Bloomberg |date=May 7, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Ashley |last2=Dawsey |first2=Josh |last3=Rucker |first3=Philip |title=Seven days: Inside Trump's frenetic response to the whistleblower complaint and the battle over impeachment |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/seven-days-inside-trumps-frenetic-response-to-the-whistleblower-complaint-and-the-battle-over-impeachment/2019/09/25/14ba426a-dfaa-11e9-be96-6adb81821e90_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Ukrainian and [[United States State Department]] sources have maintained that Shokin was fired for failing to address corruption, including within his office.<ref name=\"nyt 2019-11-10\" /><ref name=\"overlapped\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-anticorruption-effort-in-ukraine-overlapped-with-sons-work-in-country-11569189782|title=Biden's Anticorruption Effort in Ukraine Overlapped With Son's Work in Country|first=Alan|last=Cullison|website=The Wall Street Journal|date=September 22, 2019|url-access=subscription|quote=Messrs. Trump and Giuliani have suggested that Joe Biden pushed for the firing of Ukraine's general prosecutor, Viktor Shokin, in March 2016 to stop an investigation into Burisma. In Ukraine, government officials and anticorruption advocates say that is a misrepresentation{{nbsp}}... Mr. Shokin had dragged his feet into those investigations, Western diplomats said, and effectively squashed one in London by failing to cooperate with U.K. authorities{{nbsp}}... In a speech in 2015, the U.S. ambassador to Ukraine, Otto Pyatt, called the Ukrainian prosecutor \"an obstacle\" to anticorruption efforts |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49856788 |title=Ukraine ex-minister rejects Trump's Biden claims |date=September 27, 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Trump ordered the freezing of $391 million in military aid<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |authorlink1=Maggie Haberman |last2=Fandos |first2=Nicholas |authorlink2=Nicholas Fandos |last3=Crowley |first3=Michael |last4=Vogel |first4=Kenneth P. |authorlink4=Kenneth P. Vogel |title=Trump Said to Have Frozen Aid to Ukraine Before Call With Its Leader |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/23/us/politics/trump-un-biden-ukraine.html | newspaper =[[The New York Times]] |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref> shortly before a telephone conversation with Ukrainian President [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] in which Trump asked Zelensky to initiate an investigation of the Bidens.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |last2=Shear |first2=Michael D. |last3=Benner |first3=Katie |title=Trump Asks Ukraine's Leader to 'Do Us a Favor' and Also Urges Inquiry of Biden |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/25/us/politics/ukraine-transcript-trump.html | newspaper =The New York Times |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barrett |first1=Devlin |last2=Zapotosky |first2=Matt |last3=Leonnig |first3=Carol D. |authorlink3=Carol D. Leonnig |last4=Dawsey |first4=Josh |title=Trump offered Ukrainian president Justice Dept. help for Biden investigation, memo shows |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/transcript-of-trumps-call-with-ukrainian-president-shows-him-offering-us-assistance-for-biden-investigation/2019/09/25/16aa36ca-df0f-11e9-8dc8-498eabc129a0_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Trump falsely told Zelensky that \"[Joe] Biden went around bragging that he stopped the prosecution\" of his son; Joe Biden did not stop any prosecution, did not brag about doing so, and there is no evidence his son was ever under investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/25/politics/fact-check-trump-made-false-claim-to-ukrainian-president-to-justify-his-biden-request/index.html |title=Fact check: Trump made false claim to Ukrainian president to justify his Biden request |first=Daniel |last=Dale |first2=Marshall |last2=Cohen |date=September 25, 2019 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> On September 24, 2019, the [[United States House of Representatives]] initiated a formal [[impeachment in the United States|impeachment]] inquiry against Trump on the grounds that he may have sought to use U.S. foreign aid and the Ukrainian government to damage Joe Biden's [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fandos |first1=Nicholas |authorlink1=Nicholas Fandos |title=Nancy Pelosi Announces Formal Impeachment Inquiry of Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/us/politics/democrats-impeachment-trump.html | newspaper =[[The New York Times]] |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='No Pressure,' Trump Insists, While Sitting With Ukraine's Zelensky at U.N. |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/trump-sitting-ukraine-zelensky-united-nations-889491/ |first=Tessa |last=Stuart |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUkrainian prosecutor general [[Yuriy Lutsenko]] said in May 2019 that Hunter Biden had not violated Ukrainian law. After Lutsenko was replaced by [[Ruslan Riaboshapka]] as prosecutor general, Lutsenko and Ryaboshapka said in September and October 2019 respectively that they had seen no evidence of wrongdoing by Hunter Biden.<ref name=\"kiely\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilkinson |first1=Tracy |last2=Loiko |first2=Sergei |title=Former Ukraine prosecutor says he saw no evidence of wrongdoing by Biden |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2019-09-29/former-ukraine-prosecutor-says-no-wrongdoing-biden |accessdate=October 5, 2019 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine to review cases on gas firm linked to Joe Biden's son |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/ukraine-reviews-cases-gas-firm-linked-joe-biden-son-191004150913400.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2019 and into 2020, Republican senators [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]] and [[Chuck Grassley]] quietly investigated Biden's involvement with Burisma, as well as allegations that Democrats colluded with the Ukrainian government to interfere in the 2016 election. Republican senator [[Richard Burr]], chairman of the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]], privately expressed concerns to the senators that their inquiries could assist efforts by Russian intelligence to spread disinformation to disrupt American domestic affairs. American intelligence officials briefed senators in late 2019 about Russian efforts to frame Ukraine for 2016 election interference. Johnson said he would release findings in spring 2020, as Democrats would be selecting their 2020 presidential nominee. Trump tweeted a press report about the investigations, later stating that he would make allegations of corruption by the Bidens a central theme of his re-election campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/biden-trump-burisma-investigation.html|title=Republicans, Egged On by Trump, Scrutinize Hunter Biden as His Father Surges|first=Nicholas|last=Fandos|date=March 5, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/22/us/politics/ukraine-russia-interference.html|title=Charges of Ukrainian Meddling? A Russian Operation, U.S. Intelligence Says|first1=Julian E.|last1=Barnes|first2=Matthew|last2=Rosenberg|date=November 22, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Johnson sought to subpoena Andrii Telizhenko, an ally of Trump's personal attorney [[Rudy Giuliani]] and a former contractor with a public affairs firm that had worked for Burisma, but in March 2020 abruptly postponed a [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Homeland Security Committee]] vote on the subpoena, ostensibly to allow committee members to receive additional briefings on the matter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/subpoena-vote-canceled-joe-biden/index.html|title=Senate panel scraps subpoena in probe related to Bidens|author1=Jeremy Herb |author2=Marshall Cohen|website=CNN}}</ref> CNN reported that the day before the scheduled vote the FBI briefed committee staffers on issues related to Telizhenko's subpoena. A Ukrainian magazine editor told CNN that in 2018 Telizhenko offered him money to lobby Republican senators in support of pro-Russian television stations in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/europe/andrii-telizhenko-ukraine-biden-giuliani-intl/index.html|title=A Giuliani ally offered cash to lobby US senators on behalf of pro-Russian TV stations|first=Nina |last=dos Santos|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n====CEFC China Energy====\n\nBiden helped Chinese businessman [[Ye Jianming]] negotiate a deal for Ye's company [[CEFC China Energy]] to make a $40 million investment in a [[liquefied natural gas]] project at Monkey Island, [[Louisiana]]. Ye gifted Biden a 2.8 [[carat (mass)|carat]] [[diamond]], which Biden said he gave away. Biden agreed to legally represent Ye's deputy, [[Patrick Ho]], for investigations in the United States. Ho was eventually arrested and jailed in the U.S. for bribery. In 2018, the CEFC deal collapsed after Ye was detained in China, reportedly for corruption.<ref name=entous1/><ref name=bschrekinger1/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBiden married Kathleen Buhle in 1993,<ref name=\"entous1\" /> and they have three children, Naomi, Finnegan, and Maisy.<ref name=\"newman1\" /> The couple separated in 2015 and divorced in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pagesix.com/2017/04/14/hunter-and-kathleen-biden-finalize-divorce/|title=Hunter and Kathleen Biden finalize divorce |first=Julia |last=Marsh |website=[[Page Six]] |date=April 14, 2017 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> In 2016, he began dating Hallie Biden, the widow of his brother, Beau;<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Diana |last=Pearl |url=https://people.com/politics/hallie-bidens-father-says-he-supports-her-relationship-with-hunter-biden-her-late-husbands-brother/ |title=Hallie Biden's Father Says He Supports Her Relationship with Hunter Biden, Her Late Husband's Brother |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=March 2, 2017 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> they ended their relationship by late 2017 or early 2018.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Entous |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/07/08/will-hunter-biden-jeopardize-his-fathers-campaign |title=Will Hunter Biden Jeopardize His Father's Campaign? |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=July 1, 2019 |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/05/hunter-and-hallie-biden-break-up|title=Hunter Biden Has Reportedly Broken Up with His Late Brother's Wife|first=Tina|last=Nguyen|date=May 1, 2019|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Biden is also the father of a child born out of wedlock in Arkansas in August 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.texarkanagazette.com/news/arkansas/story/2020/jan/08/judge-signs-order-declaring-paternity-hunter-biden-case/811239/|website=Texarkana Gazette|title=Judge signs order declaring paternity in Hunter Biden case|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> In May 2019, Biden married Melissa Cohen, a South African filmmaker.<ref>{{cite news |first=Meredith |last=Newman |date=July 1, 2019 |url=https://delawareonline.com/story/news/2019/07/01/hunter-biden-talks-his-addiction-i-darkness/1615964001/ |title=Hunter Biden talks about his addiction, 'I was in that darkness' |work=[[The News-Journal]] |location=Wilmington, Delaware |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Heil |first1=Emily |title=Hunter Biden's messy personal life is back in the news. Will it cause political headaches for his dad? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/06/12/hunter-biden-married-los-angeles-woman-after-split-with-his-brothers-widow/?noredirect=on |website=The Washington Post |date=June 12, 2019 |accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBiden spent decades struggling with alcohol and drug addiction. He said, \"There's addiction in every family. I was in that darkness. I was in that tunnel\u2014it's a never-ending tunnel. You don't get rid of it. You figure out how to deal with it.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/07/08/will-hunter-biden-jeopardize-his-fathers-campaign |title=Will Hunter Biden Jeopardize His Father's Campaign? |last=Entous |first=Adam |date=July 1, 2019 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Newman |first1=Meredith |last2=Jagtiani |first2=Sarika |last3=Sharp |first3=Andrew |title=Hunter Biden: Who is former Vice President Joe Biden's son mentioned in Ukraine-Trump call? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/09/26/who-hunter-biden-joe-biden-son-ukraine-call/3773527002/ |work=[[The News Journal]] |location=Wilmington, Delaware |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Robert Biden}}\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/us/politics/biden-son-ukraine.html Much-referenced May 2019 story in ''The New York Times'' on Bidens, Burisma, and possible appearance of conflict-of-interest]\n\n{{Joe Biden|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biden, Hunter}}\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Biden family|Hunter]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Delaware]]\n[[Category:Connecticut lawyers]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Wilmington, Delaware]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Son of former Vice President of the United States Joe Biden}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Hunter Biden\n|image        = R. Hunter Biden at Center for Strategic & International Studies.jpg\n|caption      = Biden at the [[Center for Strategic & International Studies]] in 2013\n|office       = Vice Chairman of the [[Amtrak|National Railroad Passenger Corporation]]\n|president    = George W. Bush<br>[[Barack Obama]]\n|term_start   = July 26, 2006\n|term_end     = January 29, 2009\n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = Donna McLean\n|birth_name   = Robert Hunter Biden\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1970|2|4}}\n|birth_place  = [[Wilmington, Delaware]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Kathleen Buhle|1993|2017|end=div}}<br>{{marriage|Melissa Cohen|2019}}\n|partner      = Hallie Olivere (2016\u20132018)\n|children     = 4\n|relatives    = [[Joe Biden]] (father)<br>''See [[Biden family]]''\n|education    = [[Georgetown University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|allegiance   = {{flagu|United States}}\n|branch       = {{flag|United States Navy}}\n|serviceyears = 2013\u20132014\n|rank         = [[File:US Navy O1 infobox.svg|25px]] [[Ensign (United States)|Ensign]]\n|unit         = [[United States Navy Reserve]]\n}}\n'''Robert Hunter Biden''' (born February 4, 1970) is an American lawyer and lobbyist who is the second son of former [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Joe Biden]]. He co-founded Rosemont Seneca Partners, an international consulting firm, in 2009.\n\nBiden served on the board of [[Burisma Holdings]], a major [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] [[natural gas]] producer, from 2014 to 2019. He has been the subject of debunked right-wing [[conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] concerning his business dealings in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/in-depth/news/world/2019/10/10/trumps-biden-ukraine-natural-gas-conspiracy-theory-false-but-alive/3851728002/|title=Trump's Biden-Ukraine natural gas conspiracy theory: False, but alive|website=USA Today |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/sep/30/trump-impeachment-five-conspiracy-theories-ukraine-dilemma|title=Five fantasies Trump is pushing about the Ukraine scandal \u2013 and the truth |website=The Guardian |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/trump-impeachment-inquiry/trump-pushing-baseless-conspiracy-about-bidens-china-here-s-what-n1062551|title=Trump is pushing a baseless conspiracy about the Bidens and China. Here's what we know. |publisher=NBC News |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/there-s-no-evidence-trump-s-biden-ukraine-accusations-what-n1057851|title=There's no evidence for Trump's Biden-Ukraine accusations. What really happened?|publisher=NBC News |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/9/23/20879611/joe-biden-hunter-biden-ukraine-corruption-prosecutor-burisma-donald-trump-whistleblower-complaint|title=The facts behind Trump's bogus accusations about Biden and Ukraine|website=Vox |access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/the-invention-of-the-conspiracy-theory-on-biden-and-ukraine|title=The Invention of the Conspiracy Theory on Biden and Ukraine|website=The New Yorker |access-date=2019-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/internet/sondland-testified-misleading-ukraine-story-spread-among-conservatives-social-media-n1087511|title=As Sondland testified, a misleading Ukraine story spread among conservatives on social media|publisher=NBC News |access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> [[Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal|President Donald Trump's alleged attempt to pressure the Ukrainian government]] to investigate Joe Biden and Hunter Biden by withholding foreign aid<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/24/donald-trump-ukraine-military-aid-1509070|title=Trump changes story on withholding Ukraine aid|last=Forgey|first=Quint|website=[[Politico]]|date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/giuliani-says-he-can-t-be-100-percent-sure-trump-n1057561|title=Trump suggests he tied Ukraine funding to corruption, cites Biden allegations|last1=Pettypiece|first1=Shannon|last2=Smith|first2=Allan|date=September 23, 2019|publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/9/20/20875471/rudy-giuliani-chris-cuomo-cnn-meltdown-trump-ukraine-cnn |title=Rudy Giuliani's viral CNN meltdown over Trump and Ukraine, briefly explained |last=Rupar |first=Aaron |date=September 20, 2019 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |accessdate=September 20, 2019}}</ref> triggered an [[impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|impeachment inquiry]] in September 2019.\n\nIn October 2019, Biden resigned from the Board of Directors of a Chinese private investment fund he co-founded, [[BHR Partners]], saying he wanted to avoid even the appearance of a conflict of interest while his father was running for president.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/10/13/20912336/hunter-biden-resigns-chinese-firm-impeachment-inquiry-joe-trump|title=Hunter Biden resigns from a Chinese firm amid controversy over his business dealings|website=Vox|last=van Wagtendonk|first=Anya|date=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=CNBC191013/>\n\n==Early life==\n{{Further|Biden family}}\nBiden was born on February 4, 1970,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/hunter-biden-denies-ashley-madison-account-belongs/story?id=33301506|title=Hunter Biden Denies Ashley Madison Account Is His |first1=Jordyn |last1=Phelps |first2=Arlette |last2=Saenz |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=August 25, 2015 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> in [[Wilmington, Delaware]]. He is the second son of Neilia Biden (n\u00e9e Hunter) and [[Joe Biden]], who served in the [[United States Senate]] from 1973 to 2009 and as [[Vice President of the United States]] from 2009 to 2017.<ref name=\"entous1\">{{cite news |last1=Entous |first1=Adam |title=Will Hunter Biden Jeopardize His Father's Campaign? |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/07/08/will-hunter-biden-jeopardize-his-fathers-campaign |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=July 1, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Hunter Biden's mother and younger sister, Naomi, were killed in an automobile crash on December 18, 1972.<ref>{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Connelly |title=Biden shows more bark than bite |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7585384.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |location=London, England |date= August 28, 2008 |accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=John M.|last=Broder|title=Biden Opens New Phase With Attack on McCain |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/28/us/politics/28biden.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date= August 28, 2008|accessdate=May 7, 2014}}</ref> Biden and his older brother [[Beau Biden|Beau]] were also seriously injured.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> Hunter and Beau Biden later encouraged their father to marry again,<ref>{{cite news |first=Katharine Q.|last=Seelye|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/25/us/politics/25wife.html |title=Jill Biden Heads Toward Life in the Spotlight |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 24, 2008 |accessdate=August 25, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081210193454/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/25/us/politics/25wife.html |archivedate=December 10, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Jill Biden|Jill Jacobs]] became Hunter and Beau's stepmother in 1977.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> Biden's half-sister, Ashley, was born in 1981.<ref name=\"newman1\">{{cite news |last1=Newman |first1=Meredith |last2=Jagtiani |first2=Sarika |last3=Sharp |first3=Andrew |title=Hunter Biden: Who is former Vice President Joe Biden's son mentioned in Ukraine-Trump call? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/09/26/who-hunter-biden-joe-biden-son-ukraine-call/3773527002/ |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLike his father and brother, Biden attended [[Archmere Academy]], a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] high school in [[Claymont, Delaware]].<ref name=\"entous1\" /> In 1992, he graduated from [[Georgetown University]] with a bachelor's degree in history.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> During the year after he graduated from college, he served as a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] volunteer at a church in [[Portland, Oregon]], where he met Kathleen Buhle, whom he married in 1993.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> After attending [[Georgetown University Law Center]] for one year, he transferred to [[Yale Law School]], graduating in 1996.<ref name=\"entous1\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Early positions, 1996\u20132009===\n\nAfter graduating from law school, Biden took a position at [[MBNA]] America, a major [[bank holding]] company which was also a major contributor to his father's political campaigns.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> By 1998, he had risen to the rank of executive vice president.<ref name=\"entous1\" /><ref>{{cite news |first1=Matthew |last1=Yglesias |authorlink1=Matthew Yglesias |title=Hunter Biden, the black sheep who might accidentally bring down Trump, explained |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2019/10/1/20891510/hunter-biden-burisma-ukraine-shokin |work=Vox |date=October 1, 2019 |accessdate=October 24, 2019 |quote=There's no reason to think that Biden backed MBNA's position because his son worked there \u2014 senators normally line up with their home state's major employers' policy priorities \u2014 it's more like Hunter got the job due to his dad's overall cozy relationship with the company.}}</ref> From 1998 to 2001, he served in the [[United States Department of Commerce]], focusing on [[ecommerce]] policy.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peligri |first1=Justin |title=Who is Hunter Biden? |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2014/10/17/politics/who-is-hunter-biden/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=October 18, 2014 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Biden became a lobbyist in 2001, co-founding the firm of Oldaker, Biden & Belair.<ref name=\"bschrekinger1\" /> According to Adam Entous of ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Biden and his father established a relationship in which \"Biden wouldn't ask Hunter about his lobbying clients, and Hunter wouldn't tell his father about them.\"<ref name=\"entous1\" /> In 2006, Biden and his uncle, James Biden, attempted to buy Paradigm, a hedge-fund group, but the deal fell apart before completion.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> That same year he was appointed by President [[George W. Bush]] to a five year term on the board of directors of [[Amtrak]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Glass |first=Andrew |date=February 7, 2007 |title=A Younger Biden Goes the Extra Miles for Amtrak |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2007/02/a-younger-biden-goes-the-extra-miles-for-amtrak-002672 |work=Politico |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> He was a board member from July 2006 until he resigned in February 2009,<ref>{{cite news |last=Seitz |first=Amanda |date=October 21, 2019 |title=Hunter Biden didn't make millions off Amtrak |url=https://apnews.com/afs:Content:8002831726 |publisher=Associated Press}}</ref> and the board's vice chairman from July 2006 to January 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pennfedbmwe.org/Docs/amtrak/Amtrak_Board/McLean/20090130_Amtrak_Advisory_McLean.pdf |title=Amtrak Board Names Thomas Carper of Illinois as Chairman: Former Chairman Donna McLean Becomes Vice Chairman |date=January 30, 2009 |website=pennfedbmwe.org |publisher=National Railroad Passenger Corporation |location=Washington, D.C. |page=1}}</ref> leaving both roles shortly after his father became vice president. He had realized during his father's vice presidential campaign that it was time for his lobbying activities to end.<ref name=\"entous1\" />\n\n===Later career, 2009\u2013present===\nIn 2009, Biden, along with Devon Archer and [[John Kerry]]'s stepson [[Christopher Heinz]], founded the investment firm Rosemont Seneca.<ref name=\"bschrekinger1\">{{cite news |last1=Schrekinger |first1=Ben |title=Biden Inc. |url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/08/02/joe-biden-investigation-hunter-brother-hedge-fund-money-2020-campaign-227407 |work=Politico Magazine |date=August 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe also joined the law firm [[Boies Schiller Flexner LLP]],<ref name=\"entous1\" /> and founded Eudora Global, a venture capital firm.<ref name=\"newman1\" />\n\n====U.S. Navy Reserve====\nIn May 2013, Biden's application for a position in the [[U.S. Navy Reserve]] was approved.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-son-hunter-discharged-from-navy-reserve-after-failing-cocaine-test-1413499657|title=Biden's Son Hunter Discharged From Navy Reserve After Failing Cocaine Test|last=Nelson|first=Colleen McCain|date=October 16, 2014|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |last2=Barnes |first2=Julian E. |issn=0099-9660 |access-date=May 3, 2019}}</ref> At age 43, Biden was accepted as part of a program that allows a limited number of applicants with desirable skills to receive commissions and serve in staff positions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ziezulewicz |first=Geoff |date=October 25, 2019 |title=The people Priebus beat out to become an ensign |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-navy/2019/10/25/the-people-priebus-beat-out-to-become-an-ensign/ |work=Military Times |location=Springfield, VA}}</ref> He received an age-related waiver and a waiver due to a past drug-related incident, and was sworn in as a [[direct commission officer]].<ref name=\"wsj\" /> Joe Biden administered his commissioning oath in a [[White House]] ceremony.<ref name=\"entous1\" />\n\nThe following month, Biden tested positive for [[cocaine]] during a urinalysis test and was subsequently discharged.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/article/1618324/us-navy-expelled-vice-president-bidens-son-after-positive-cocaine-test |agency=Agence France-Presse |title=US Navy expelled Vice-President Biden's son after positive cocaine test|date=October 17, 2014|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|accessdate=October 17, 2014}}</ref> Biden attributed the result to smoking cigarettes he had accepted from other smokers, only later suspecting they had been laced with the drug.<ref name=\"entous1\" /> He chose not to appeal the matter as it was unlikely that the panel would believe his explanation given his history with drugs, and also due to the likelihood of news leaking to the press, though it was ultimately revealed to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' by a Navy official who provided information to the newspaper on condition of anonymity.<ref name=\"entous1\" /><ref name=\"wsj\" />\n\n====BHR Partners====\nIn 2013, Biden, Devon Archer, and Chinese businessman Jonathan Li founded [[BHR Partners]], a business focused on investing Chinese capital in companies based outside of [[China]].<ref name=\"entous1\" /> In September 2019, President Trump falsely claimed that Biden \"walk[ed] out of China with $1.5 billion in a fund\" and earned \"millions\" of dollars from the BHR deal, while Trump was also accusing Biden of malfeasance in Ukraine.<ref name=\"kessler-china\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/09/26/trumps-false-claims-about-hunter-bidens-china-dealings/|title=Trump's false claims about Hunter Biden's China dealings |first=Glenn |last=Kessler |authorlink=Glenn Kessler (journalist) |date=September 26, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/politics/fact-check-trump-bidens-china/index.html |date=October 4, 2019 |title=Fact-checking Trump's claims about the Bidens in China |first=Tara |last=Subramaniam |publisher=CNN |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Trump publicly called on China to investigate Hunter Biden's business activities there while his father was vice president.<ref>{{cite news |title=Explainer: Trump's claims and Hunter Biden's dealings in China |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-whistleblower-hunterbiden-c/explainer-trumps-claims-and-hunter-bidens-dealings-in-china-idUSKBN1WI2HK |agency=Reuters |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=What We Know About Hunter Biden's Business in China |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/03/us/politics/hunter-biden-china.html |first=Sharon |last=LaFraniere |authorlink=Sharon LaFraniere |first2=Michael |last2=Forsythe |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 3, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> On October 13, 2019, citing \"the barrage of false charges\" by the President, Hunter Biden announced his resignation from the Board of Directors for BHR Partners effective at the end of the month.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=David |title=Hunter Biden to step down from board of Chinese company |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/13/hunter-biden-resign-china-company-045761 |work=Politico |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref><ref name=CNBC191013>{{cite news |last1=Newburger |first1=Emma |title=Hunter Biden resigns from Chinese firm following Trump attacks |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/10/13/hunter-biden-resigns-from-chinese-firm-following-trump-attacks.html |publisher=CNBC |date=October 13, 2019 |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref> According to his lawyer, Biden had \"not received any compensation for being on BHR's board of directors,\" nor had he received any return on his equity share in BHR.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://medium.com/@george.mesires/a-statement-on-behalf-of-hunter-biden-dated-october-13-2019-d80bc11087ab |title=A Statement on behalf of Hunter Biden, dated October 13, 2019 |last=Mesires |first=George |website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |date=October 13, 2019 |accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref> Biden's lawyer, George Mesires, told ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that BHR Partners had been \"capitalized from various sources with a total of 30 million RMB [Chinese [[Renminbi]]], or about $4.2 million, not $1.5 billion.\"<ref name=\"kessler-china\" />\n\n====Burisma Holdings====\nIn April 2014 after the [[2014 Ukrainian revolution|Ukrainian revolution]], Biden joined the board of [[Burisma Holdings]], one of the largest independent natural gas producers in [[Ukraine]]<ref name=\"entous1\" /> owned by an [[Ukrainian oligarch]] and former politician [[Mykola Zlochevsky]] who faced a money laundering investigation that time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/12/the-money-machine-how-a-high-profile-corruption-investigation-fell-apart |title=The money machine: how a high-profile corruption investigation fell apart |last=Bullough |first=Oliver |date=April 12, 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"sonne1\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Risen |first=James |authorlink=James Risen |date=December 8, 2015 |title=Joe Biden, His Son and the Case Against a Ukrainian Oligarch |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/09/world/europe/corruption-ukraine-joe-biden-son-hunter-biden-ties.html | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref> Biden, then an attorney with [[Boies Schiller Flexner LLP|Boies Schiller Flexner]], was hired to help Burisma with [[corporate governance]] [[best practice]]s, and a consulting firm in which Biden is a partner was also retained by Burisma.<ref name=nyt220919>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/22/us/politics/biden-ukraine-trump.html|title=Trump, Biden and Ukraine: Sorting Out the Accusations|first=Kenneth P.|last=Vogel|date=September 22, 2019|newspaper=The New York Times | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"vogel-nyt\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/us/politics/biden-son-ukraine.html|title=Biden Faces Conflict of Interest Questions That Are Being Promoted by Trump and Allies|last=Vogel|first=Kenneth P.|date=May 1, 2019| newspaper =[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 29, 2019 | url-access = subscription |url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/b3Kow|archive-date=May 4, 2019|last2=Mendel|first2=Iuliia |issn=0362-4331|authorlink=Kenneth P. Vogel|author-link2=Iuliia Mendel}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2019/sep/23/president-donald-trump-ukraine-biden-whistleblower/|title=Trump's Ukraine call, a whistleblower and the Bidens: What we know, what we don't|last=Jacobson|first=Louis|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=September 24, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924204438/https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2019/sep/23/president-donald-trump-ukraine-biden-whistleblower/|archive-date=September 24, 2019|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|last2=Kruzel|first2=John}}</ref> Chris Heinz, [[John Kerry]]'s stepson, opposed his partners Devon Archer and Hunter Biden joining the board in 2014 due to the [[reputational risk]].<ref name=\"sonne1\" /> Biden served on the board of Burisma until his term expired in April 2019,<ref name=\"vogel-nyt\"/> receiving compensation of up to $50,000 per month in some months.<ref name=\"vogel-nyt\" /><ref name=nyt220919/> Because Vice President Biden played a major role in U.S. policy towards Ukraine, some Ukrainian anti-corruption advocates<ref name=\"braun1\" /><ref name=\"overlapped\" /> and [[presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] officials expressed concern that Hunter Biden's having joined the board could create the appearance of a [[conflict of interest]] and undermine Vice President Biden's anti-corruption work in Ukraine.<ref name=\"entous1\" /><ref name=\"sonne1\">{{cite news |last1=Sonne |first1=Paul |last2=Kranish |first2=Michael |last3=Viser |first3=Matt |title=The gas tycoon and the vice president's son: The story of Hunter Biden's foray into Ukraine |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/the-gas-tycoon-and-the-vice-presidents-son-the-story-of-hunter-bidens-foray-in-ukraine/2019/09/28/1aadff70-dfd9-11e9-8fd3-d943b4ed57e0_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 28, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> While serving as vice president, Joe Biden joined other Western leaders in encouraging the government of Ukraine to fire the country's top prosecutor, [[Viktor Shokin]],<ref name=\"kiely\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bump |first1=Philip |last2=Blake |first2=Aaron |title=The full Trump-Ukraine timeline \u2014 as of now |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/09/24/full-trump-ukraine-timeline-now/ |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> who was widely criticized for blocking corruption investigations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Daniel |title=EU hails sacking of Ukraine's prosecutor Viktor Shokin |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/eu-hails-sacking-of-ukraine-s-prosecutor-viktor-shokin-1.2591190 |work=The Irish Times |date=March 29, 2016 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/23/us/politics/trump-ukraine-collusion.html|title=Instead of 'No Collusion!' Trump Now Seems to Be Saying, So What if I Did?|first=Peter|last=Baker|authorlink=Peter Baker (journalist) |date=September 23, 2019|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019 | url-access = subscription}}</ref> The [[Verkhovna Rada|Ukrainian parliament]] voted to remove Shokin in March 2016.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://iportal.rada.gov.ua/en/news/News/page/en/news/News/127271.html |date=March 29, 2016 |title=News - Verkhovna Rada Chairperson Volodymyr Groysman calls on all people's deputies to take part in voting for dismissal of prosecutor general Shokin - Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine |website=iportal.rada.gov.ua|access-date=September 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/10/02/correcting-media-error-bidens-ukraine-showdown-was-december/ |title=Correcting a media error: Biden's Ukraine showdown was in December 2015 |last=Kessler |first=Glenn |authorlink=Glenn Kessler (journalist) |website=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 2, 2019 |accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, President Donald Trump and his personal lawyer, [[Rudy Giuliani]], claimed that Vice President Biden had actually sought the dismissal of Shokin in order to protect his son and Burisma Holdings,<ref name=\"raymond1\">{{cite news |last1=Raymond |first1=Adam K. |title=Everything We Know About the Joe Biden\u2013Ukraine Controversy |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/05/joe-biden-ukraine-controversy.html |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=May 7, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"braun1\">{{cite news |last1=Braun |first1=Stephen |last2=Berry |first2=Lynn |title=The story behind Biden's son, Ukraine and Trump's claims |url=https://www.apnews.com/9d4595ba4f3140c6bb6a3473a91f4a4c |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 23, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> however, there is no evidence that this was what happened and it was the official policy of the United States and the European Union to seek Shokin's removal.<ref name=\"kiely\">{{cite news |last1=Kiely |first1=Eugene |title=Trump Twists Facts on Biden and Ukraine |url=https://www.factcheck.org/2019/09/trump-twists-facts-on-biden-and-ukraine/ |work=[[FactCheck.org]] |publisher=Annenberg Public Policy Center |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt 2019-11-10\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/us/politics/joe-biden-ukraine.html|title=What Joe Biden Actually Did in Ukraine|first1=Glenn|last1=Thrush|first2=Kenneth P.|last2=Vogel|date=November 10, 2019 |newspaper=The New York Times | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref>In March 2016 testimony to the [[Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], former ambassador to Ukraine [[John E. Herbst]] stated, \"By late fall of 2015, the EU and the United States joined the chorus of those seeking Mr. Shokin\u2019s removal\" and that Joe Biden \"spoke publicly about this before and during his December visit to Kyiv.\" During the same hearing, assistant secretary of state [[Victoria Nuland]] stated, \"we have pegged our next $1 billion loan guarantee, first and foremost, to having a rebooting of the reform coalition so that we know who we are working with, but secondarily, to ensuring that the prosecutor general\u2019s office gets cleaned up.\" https://www.foreign.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/03%2015%2016%20Ukrainian%20Reforms%20Two%20Years%20After%20the%20Maidan%20Revolution%20and%20the%20Russian%20Invasion.pdf</ref> There has also been no evidence produced of wrongdoing done by Hunter Biden in Ukraine.<ref>Multiple sources:\n*{{cite news |title=Trump: I want to meet my accuser |url=https://www.afp.com/en/news/3954/trump-i-want-meet-my-accuser-doc-1kt4vy4 |date=September 30, 2019 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=US President Donald Trump said on Sunday he wants and deserves to meet the anonymous whistleblower at the center of the fast-moving scandal that has triggered an impeachment probe against him ... Brandishing what he said were affidavits incriminating Biden's son Hunter over his work at a Ukrainian company, Giuliani said Trump was duty bound to raise the issue with Kiev. Trump and his allies claim Biden, as Barack Obama's vice president, pressured Kiev to fire the country's top prosecutor to protect his son Hunter, who sat on the board of a gas company, Burisma Holdings, accused of corrupt practices. Those allegations have largely been debunked and there has been no evidence of illegal conduct or wrongdoing in Ukraine by the Bidens.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Matthias |first1=Williams |last2=Polityuk |first2=Pavel |title=Zelenskiy opponents say comments about Europeans to Trump could hurt Ukraine |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/usa-trump-whistleblower-lawmaker-idAFL5N26H3HV |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=Trump pressed Zelenskiy to investigate the business dealings of the son of his political rival, former Vice President Joe Biden, the Democratic front-runner to challenge Trump in an election next year. Zelenskiy agreed. Biden's son Hunter worked for a company drilling for gas in Ukraine. There has been no evidence of wrongdoing by either Biden.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Isachenkov |first1=Vladimir |title=Ukraine's prosecutor says there is no probe into Biden |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/ukraines-prosecutor-says-there-is-no-probe-into-biden |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=September 27, 2019 |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=Though the timing raised concerns among anti-corruption advocates, there has been no evidence of wrongdoing by either the former vice president or his son.}}\n*{{cite news |title=White House 'tried to cover up details of Trump-Ukraine call' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49842895 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate= October 1, 2019 |quote=There is no evidence of any wrongdoing by the Bidens.}}\n*{{cite news |last1=Timm |first1=Jane |title=There's no evidence for Trump's Biden-Ukraine accusations. What really happened? |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/there-s-no-evidence-trump-s-biden-ukraine-accusations-what-n1057851 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 1, 2019 |quote=But despite Trump's continued claims, there's no evidence of wrongdoing on the part of either Biden.}}</ref> The Ukrainian anti-corruption investigation agency stated in September 2019 that the ''current'' investigation of Burisma was restricted solely to investigating the period of 2010 to 2012, before Hunter Biden joined Burisma in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ivanova |first1=Polina |last2=Polityuk |first2=Pavel |title=Ukraine agency says allegations against Burisma cover period before Biden joined |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-whistleblower-ukraine-buris/ukraine-agency-says-allegations-against-burisma-cover-period-before-biden-joined-idUSKBN1WC1LV |date=September 27, 2019 |agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> Shokin in May 2019 claimed that he was fired because he had been actively investigating Burisma,<ref name=\"baker1\" /> but U.S. and Ukrainian officials have stated that the investigation into Burisma was dormant at the time of Shokin's dismissal.<ref name=\"sonne1\" /><ref name=\"baker1\">{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Stephanie |last2=Krasnolutska |first2=Daryna |title=Timeline in Ukraine Probe Casts Doubt on Giuliani's Biden Claim |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-07/timeline-in-ukraine-probe-casts-doubt-on-giuliani-s-biden-claim |work=Bloomberg |date=May 7, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Ashley |last2=Dawsey |first2=Josh |last3=Rucker |first3=Philip |title=Seven days: Inside Trump's frenetic response to the whistleblower complaint and the battle over impeachment |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/seven-days-inside-trumps-frenetic-response-to-the-whistleblower-complaint-and-the-battle-over-impeachment/2019/09/25/14ba426a-dfaa-11e9-be96-6adb81821e90_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Ukrainian and [[United States State Department]] sources have maintained that Shokin was fired for failing to address corruption, including within his office.<ref name=\"nyt 2019-11-10\" /><ref name=\"overlapped\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-anticorruption-effort-in-ukraine-overlapped-with-sons-work-in-country-11569189782|title=Biden's Anticorruption Effort in Ukraine Overlapped With Son's Work in Country|first=Alan|last=Cullison|website=The Wall Street Journal|date=September 22, 2019|url-access=subscription|quote=Messrs. Trump and Giuliani have suggested that Joe Biden pushed for the firing of Ukraine's general prosecutor, Viktor Shokin, in March 2016 to stop an investigation into Burisma. In Ukraine, government officials and anticorruption advocates say that is a misrepresentation{{nbsp}}... Mr. Shokin had dragged his feet into those investigations, Western diplomats said, and effectively squashed one in London by failing to cooperate with U.K. authorities{{nbsp}}... In a speech in 2015, the U.S. ambassador to Ukraine, Otto Pyatt, called the Ukrainian prosecutor \"an obstacle\" to anticorruption efforts |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-49856788 |title=Ukraine ex-minister rejects Trump's Biden claims |date=September 27, 2019 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Trump ordered the freezing of $391 million in military aid<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |authorlink1=Maggie Haberman |last2=Fandos |first2=Nicholas |authorlink2=Nicholas Fandos |last3=Crowley |first3=Michael |last4=Vogel |first4=Kenneth P. |authorlink4=Kenneth P. Vogel |title=Trump Said to Have Frozen Aid to Ukraine Before Call With Its Leader |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/23/us/politics/trump-un-biden-ukraine.html | newspaper =[[The New York Times]] |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref> shortly before a telephone conversation with Ukrainian President [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] in which Trump asked Zelensky to initiate an investigation of the Bidens.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haberman |first1=Maggie |last2=Shear |first2=Michael D. |last3=Benner |first3=Katie |title=Trump Asks Ukraine's Leader to 'Do Us a Favor' and Also Urges Inquiry of Biden |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/25/us/politics/ukraine-transcript-trump.html | newspaper =The New York Times |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barrett |first1=Devlin |last2=Zapotosky |first2=Matt |last3=Leonnig |first3=Carol D. |authorlink3=Carol D. Leonnig |last4=Dawsey |first4=Josh |title=Trump offered Ukrainian president Justice Dept. help for Biden investigation, memo shows |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/transcript-of-trumps-call-with-ukrainian-president-shows-him-offering-us-assistance-for-biden-investigation/2019/09/25/16aa36ca-df0f-11e9-8dc8-498eabc129a0_story.html |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Trump falsely told Zelensky that \"[Joe] Biden went around bragging that he stopped the prosecution\" of his son; Joe Biden did not stop any prosecution, did not brag about doing so, and there is no evidence his son was ever under investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/25/politics/fact-check-trump-made-false-claim-to-ukrainian-president-to-justify-his-biden-request/index.html |title=Fact check: Trump made false claim to Ukrainian president to justify his Biden request |first=Daniel |last=Dale |first2=Marshall |last2=Cohen |date=September 25, 2019 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> On September 24, 2019, the [[United States House of Representatives]] initiated a formal [[impeachment in the United States|impeachment]] inquiry against Trump on the grounds that he may have sought to use U.S. foreign aid and the Ukrainian government to damage Joe Biden's [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fandos |first1=Nicholas |authorlink1=Nicholas Fandos |title=Nancy Pelosi Announces Formal Impeachment Inquiry of Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/us/politics/democrats-impeachment-trump.html | newspaper =[[The New York Times]] |date=September 24, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019  | url-access = subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='No Pressure,' Trump Insists, While Sitting With Ukraine's Zelensky at U.N. |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-news/trump-sitting-ukraine-zelensky-united-nations-889491/ |first=Tessa |last=Stuart |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=September 25, 2019 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUkrainian prosecutor general [[Yuriy Lutsenko]] said in May 2019 that Hunter Biden had not violated Ukrainian law. After Lutsenko was replaced by [[Ruslan Riaboshapka]] as prosecutor general, Lutsenko and Ryaboshapka said in September and October 2019 respectively that they had seen no evidence of wrongdoing by Hunter Biden.<ref name=\"kiely\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilkinson |first1=Tracy |last2=Loiko |first2=Sergei |title=Former Ukraine prosecutor says he saw no evidence of wrongdoing by Biden |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2019-09-29/former-ukraine-prosecutor-says-no-wrongdoing-biden |accessdate=October 5, 2019 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=September 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine to review cases on gas firm linked to Joe Biden's son |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/ukraine-reviews-cases-gas-firm-linked-joe-biden-son-191004150913400.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=October 4, 2019 |accessdate=October 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2019 and into 2020, Republican senators [[Ron Johnson (Wisconsin politician)|Ron Johnson]] and [[Chuck Grassley]] quietly investigated Biden's involvement with Burisma, as well as allegations that Democrats colluded with the Ukrainian government to interfere in the 2016 election. Republican senator [[Richard Burr]], chairman of the [[Senate Intelligence Committee]], privately expressed concerns to the senators that their inquiries could assist efforts by Russian intelligence to spread disinformation to disrupt American domestic affairs. American intelligence officials briefed senators in late 2019 about Russian efforts to frame Ukraine for 2016 election interference. Johnson said he would release findings in spring 2020, as Democrats would be selecting their 2020 presidential nominee. Trump tweeted a press report about the investigations, later stating that he would make allegations of corruption by the Bidens a central theme of his re-election campaign.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/biden-trump-burisma-investigation.html|title=Republicans, Egged On by Trump, Scrutinize Hunter Biden as His Father Surges|first=Nicholas|last=Fandos|date=March 5, 2020|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/22/us/politics/ukraine-russia-interference.html|title=Charges of Ukrainian Meddling? A Russian Operation, U.S. Intelligence Says|first1=Julian E.|last1=Barnes|first2=Matthew|last2=Rosenberg|date=November 22, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Johnson sought to subpoena Andrii Telizhenko, an ally of Trump's personal attorney [[Rudy Giuliani]] and a former contractor with a public affairs firm that had worked for Burisma, but in March 2020 abruptly postponed a [[United States Senate Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs|Homeland Security Committee]] vote on the subpoena, ostensibly to allow committee members to receive additional briefings on the matter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/subpoena-vote-canceled-joe-biden/index.html|title=Senate panel scraps subpoena in probe related to Bidens|author1=Jeremy Herb |author2=Marshall Cohen|website=CNN}}</ref> CNN reported that the day before the scheduled vote the FBI briefed committee staffers on issues related to Telizhenko's subpoena. A Ukrainian magazine editor told CNN that in 2018 Telizhenko offered him money to lobby Republican senators in support of pro-Russian television stations in Ukraine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/europe/andrii-telizhenko-ukraine-biden-giuliani-intl/index.html|title=A Giuliani ally offered cash to lobby US senators on behalf of pro-Russian TV stations|first=Nina |last=dos Santos|website=CNN}}</ref>\n\n====CEFC China Energy====\n\nBiden helped Chinese businessman [[Ye Jianming]] negotiate a deal for Ye's company [[CEFC China Energy]] to make a $40 million investment in a [[liquefied natural gas]] project at Monkey Island, [[Louisiana]]. Ye gifted Biden a 2.8 [[carat (mass)|carat]] [[diamond]], which Biden said he gave away. Biden agreed to legally represent Ye's deputy, [[Patrick Ho]], for investigations in the United States. Ho was eventually arrested and jailed in the U.S. for bribery. In 2018, the CEFC deal collapsed after Ye was detained in China, reportedly for corruption.<ref name=entous1/><ref name=bschrekinger1/>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBiden married Kathleen Buhle in 1993,<ref name=\"entous1\" /> and they have three children, Naomi, Finnegan, and Maisy.<ref name=\"newman1\" /> The couple separated in 2015 and divorced in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pagesix.com/2017/04/14/hunter-and-kathleen-biden-finalize-divorce/|title=Hunter and Kathleen Biden finalize divorce |first=Julia |last=Marsh |website=[[Page Six]] |date=April 14, 2017 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> In 2016, he began dating Hallie Biden, the widow of his brother, Beau;<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Diana |last=Pearl |url=https://people.com/politics/hallie-bidens-father-says-he-supports-her-relationship-with-hunter-biden-her-late-husbands-brother/ |title=Hallie Biden's Father Says He Supports Her Relationship with Hunter Biden, Her Late Husband's Brother |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=March 2, 2017 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> they ended their relationship by late 2017 or early 2018.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Entous |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/07/08/will-hunter-biden-jeopardize-his-fathers-campaign |title=Will Hunter Biden Jeopardize His Father's Campaign? |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=July 1, 2019 |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2019/05/hunter-and-hallie-biden-break-up|title=Hunter Biden Has Reportedly Broken Up with His Late Brother's Wife|first=Tina|last=Nguyen|date=May 1, 2019|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Biden is also the father of a child born out of wedlock in Arkansas in August 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.texarkanagazette.com/news/arkansas/story/2020/jan/08/judge-signs-order-declaring-paternity-hunter-biden-case/811239/|website=Texarkana Gazette|title=Judge signs order declaring paternity in Hunter Biden case|access-date=2020-01-11}}</ref> In May 2019, Biden married Melissa Cohen, a South African filmmaker.<ref>{{cite news |first=Meredith |last=Newman |date=July 1, 2019 |url=https://delawareonline.com/story/news/2019/07/01/hunter-biden-talks-his-addiction-i-darkness/1615964001/ |title=Hunter Biden talks about his addiction, 'I was in that darkness' |work=[[The News-Journal]] |location=Wilmington, Delaware |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Heil |first1=Emily |title=Hunter Biden's messy personal life is back in the news. Will it cause political headaches for his dad? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/06/12/hunter-biden-married-los-angeles-woman-after-split-with-his-brothers-widow/?noredirect=on |website=The Washington Post |date=June 12, 2019 |accessdate=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBiden spent decades struggling with alcohol and drug addiction. He said, \"There's addiction in every family. I was in that darkness. I was in that tunnel\u2014it's a never-ending tunnel. You don't get rid of it. You figure out how to deal with it.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/07/08/will-hunter-biden-jeopardize-his-fathers-campaign |title=Will Hunter Biden Jeopardize His Father's Campaign? |last=Entous |first=Adam |date=July 1, 2019 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=July 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Newman |first1=Meredith |last2=Jagtiani |first2=Sarika |last3=Sharp |first3=Andrew |title=Hunter Biden: Who is former Vice President Joe Biden's son mentioned in Ukraine-Trump call? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/09/26/who-hunter-biden-joe-biden-son-ukraine-call/3773527002/ |work=[[The News Journal]] |location=Wilmington, Delaware |date=September 26, 2019 |accessdate=October 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Robert Biden}}\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/us/politics/biden-son-ukraine.html Much-referenced May 2019 story in ''The New York Times'' on Bidens, Burisma, and possible appearance of conflict-of-interest]\n\n{{Joe Biden|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biden, Hunter}}\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of French descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Biden family|Hunter]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Delaware]]\n[[Category:Connecticut lawyers]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Wilmington, Delaware]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly positions, 1996\u20132009:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: five year \u2192 five-year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunter_Biden"}
